animal.description:
This is Derby Densmore. He is a purebred Boston terrier, about 22 lb, and is only 7- years old despite the grey over his eyes. This boy is happy, bouncy, and needs discipline to behave--if he has it, he's very obedient. If he doesn't have that discipline, he will take charge and will be a problem child. He needs an experienced Boston parent.
Derby is energetic to say the least. Loving, very affectionate, hearty and healthy. Needs exercise and mental stimulation--walks are great, as long as discipline is maintained--walks are important mental exercise. He would love an active person who wants to take him on adventures, not set him on a pillow. He can be dog aggressive, but will listen if he believes in his boss.

Adopter must come to North Carolina where Derby is and meet with the trainer that has been working with him. A training session is included in the adoption and the trainer has to feel confident that the adopter will follow through with techniques taught at the session.

Derby Densmore is neutered, UTD on vaccines, microchipped and heart worm negative. For more info on Derby, call his buddy, Cindy, at 919-302-6126.
The adoption fee will be $275.00 The 1st step is always an application found at: www.bostonterriertn.org (the $20 app fee is required before consideration) If you want to meet me, please call my buddy Cindy at cinjohack@bellsouth.net We prefer homes with prior Boston experience and current pet history.
NOTE: Submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston, since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

animal.description:
Awesome, Guapo, shelter favorite, Is good with male and female dogs, children and great on a leash! He is an amazing catch! Small sized about 50 pounds and awesome.
He is about 2 years young, handsome, smaller sized, mixed Staffordshire breed terrier.
He should have a knowledgeable handler and you can do anything with him and go anywhere. He currently plays with male and female dogs.
He came in a little excited, but we worked with him and now he is a perfect gentleman. We encourage adopters with experience and they will have  great dog.
He came in late November and has been a great guest.
We have more pics put need to process them to post.
We love taking him out on the leash with any dog. He loves trail walking and is sweet., easy, handsome, LEVI is a super great friend and dog! He is about 2  years old, very handsome and loving. He has been a true gentleman since he arrived at LBWF. He is super easy, and a perfect companion and dog. He loves to snuggle or play. Easy going and will be great couch company and friend!  He gets along with lots of dogs, has manners, he is handsome and a great adoption pick for you and or a family!
So handsome in his golden coat
 
The Apple Valley shelter is filled with dogs and had so many people interested in him that did a lottery drawing. The people never showed up. The shelter put him back up for adoption and we snapped him up before they closed down for the holidays. We were there during the pandemic shut down in march, with no chance to be seen for adoption. When I said I would take him, their response was,"you will love him".
He is dog friendly. Just does his thing then comes over for love. So handsome!
 He super deserves to have his forever home and a great fun loving life!. He will love the beach, camping, car rides, coffee shops and to be everything you wish for in a friend! 
He is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and micro-chipped. All he needs now is his forever loving home! If you are interested in adopting him, please fill out an application today.
Applications can be found on our website www.LindaBlairWorldheart.org under the adopt today tab. Southern, CA. adoptions only due to home checks.
Please tell us what a great life you have in store for him.

View all of our dogs available for adoption at www.LindaBlairWorldheart.org
Follow us on social media: Facebook/LindaBlairWorldheartFoundation
Instagram & Twitter @LindaBlairWF

animal.description:
Klaus was found trailing his leash and wearing a collar but no one came to claim him (nice, huh?). 
He would be best suited to a home with another dog who likes to play, as he has liked every dog he has met so far.
He is VERY timid (not an alpha!) and just afraid of everything and fast movements make him cower (what did his owner do to him?!) as do loud noises, but, in time, he will get over that, I feel sure.
He does not mess up his kennel at the clinic so maybe he is potty trained, he does pull on the leash, but will stop when you tell him to do so.
He is interested in cat in carriers, wanting to sniff them, but no idea how he might act if they were free.
Have not yet seen him around children but they possibly might scare him at first.
He needs someone to show him that humans can be loving and not mean, that they can take care of him for the rest of his life and not abandon him.
He gets so excited when a person he knows comes to see him!
UPDATED
Since he has been in foster, he has blossomed into a very playful more outgoing puppy, as he should be.
He is learning quickly how to play fetch and just learning how to DOG!
FOSTERING makes all the difference in the world in the lives of these dogs (and cats!)
He will make an amazing addition to some lucky family.

animal.description: Hello my name is Queen. I am a approximately 2 years old. I'm a special case, I've ran wild for most of my life, until 8/12 when these mysterious ladies caught me, days from giving birth. I was massively pregnant with 8 puppies, uncomfortable with human contact/presence, and in survival mode. After a few short days of being in this safe haven, I gave birth to 8 beautiful pups. My babies would help me get more comfortable with these lovely ladies who wanted to show me nothing but love. Slowly but surely I am gaining more confidence to get comfortable with human interaction. After my puppies found their forever homes, we've began to do more one on one interactions to try to boost my confidence. I am easily frightened by loud noises and fast movement. I would exceed best in a home with no other pets and no children. I need a laid back home where I will have time to adjust and time to learn to trust. Time and patience is my key needs in succeeding in becoming the best dog I can be. If you or someone you know, has the time, patience, and heart of gold to take this babe in, please contact us at 2603472563 or via Facebook messenger.

animal.description:
**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

New Chiweenie Chihuahua Dachshund, Dana She has a wonderful tail wagging personality and will kiss strangers. She is working on sharing her foster parents with the other dogs. She just gives a low growl, so this is a minor training issue she'll learn. 6-year-old Dana is 13 pounds, healthy, and ready for her devoted home. Dana walks well on the leash and would benefit from some good outings to keep her socialized and happy. Dana's adoption fee is $350 to go towards her vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, and microchip as well as grooming if needed). If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. 

 *All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. * All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health.*All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

Hey there! I'm Eve. I'm a goofy and charming senior gal looking for a loving family to live out my golden years with. Let me tell you my story. I am just over 10 years old and I was rescued from the local county shelter. It was clear to the humans that saved me that I had lived a long life of having many litters of puppies. I was thin and dirty but I didn't let my past keep me down.

Now that I'm happily living the couch life with my foster parents, they tell me I'm a big goofball with a lively spirit for my age. I absolutely love people and I am amazing with kids. The humans tell me I'm an 80 pound dog and that big dogs can't be lap dogs. I don't believe them. If you let me cuddle with you then I'm going to accept the invitation to do so. I am looking for a home where I can be the only pet since I love my humans so much I get jealous. I am really looking forward to being the center of someone's world.

I also love my stuffed toys. When my foster parents leave, I sit by the window and wait for them. I do get anxious because I don't want them to stay away long, but I know what's mine to play with in the house when I'm feeling a little upset. When they come home, I've never been happier. I check to make sure they're okay then I go straight to my toys to show them how happy I am with a few squeaks. Exploring outdoors is fun for me, which is why I'd love a porch or yard. I like doing anything my humans do. As long as my family knows I need more patience and creativity (especially with finishing all my food) than those young gals. I like treats (especially when I'm a good listener on walks), but belly rubs, head scratches, being brushed and being told I'm good are my biggest motivators. 

I have this thing called heartworms. I am currently undergoing treatment. Don't worry though I can still be adopted and would love to be your gal.

Layla is a really sweet girl. She loves being by your side and loves pets. Shes active, but also can just chill out with you as you watch tv or lie down. Shes also house trained and does well by herself. She can be reactive to other dogs on walks, but Im sure with the right training that could be fixed. 

HW+ simply means the dog has tested positive for heart worms in our screening process. We utilize what is called the fast-kill method which means we place the dog on antibiotics for 30 days and then administer 3 injections in increments afterward. The cost to treat heart worms is rather steep. However, thanks to our generous donors, we are able to cover that cost for our adopters so long as they go to our veterinarian, Red Rocks Animal Center in Lakewood.

Approved Applicants may make the adoption fee payment by clicking donate above. Partial adoption fees will not hold a dog.

If upon meeting the dog of your choosing at an adoption event you find that you aren't a good match, your deposit will be refunded minus a 10% administration fee.

In-person adoptions will begin on the date of a dog's first event provided they are still available. Dogs not adopted during their first event will attend additional events thereafter until adopted. 

An adoption application online is required prior to viewing our dogs. Adoption fees include vaccines up until time of adoption, microchip, spay/neuter and 1st 30 days of free Pet insurance. We are not affiliated with Pet First pet insurance. (you have to sign up for the insurance or it will not go into effect). Adopters can go to our vet for medical issues that may arise in 1st 3 days of adoption. 

The dogs in our care are fostered in Colorado, Texas, and New Mexico. While all dogs are picked up during our scheduled times, sometimes transport dates change due to unforeseen circumstances.

animal.description:
We are not currently accepting additional applications for Xihua; check back for updates

Animal Profile: Xihua is a 3-year-old 40lb male mixed breed who was saved from the streets of Mexico at 4 weeks old and lovingly raised with a family here in Seattle. However, unfortunately with three small kids and small animals in the home, Xihua now needs a new family. Xihua is house trained, clean and adorable but he can be aloof and is reactive to dogs on walks. While he lives with another dog without issues, he is slow to make dog friends. He does not have stranger danger but is generally anxious. He is very food motivated and trainable, and would do wonderfully as the only pet in a quiet household.

DGS Evaluation Notes: Xihua was very quick to warm up to humans (no reaction), was very responsive to correction with a slip lead giving eye contact and taking treats, and was able to walk around other balanced dogs without reaction at a distance of 10'. He could live in a home with a balanced dog and structured introductions. He will need continued leash training. He is okay with people. He has no bite history. He's adorable and a good size - 40 or so lbs.

Foster Updates: Xihua is affectionate and playful. He has not been aloof as far as we have seen at all. He has a vigorous play style! He will react on leash to reactive dogs and will need continued training in this department. He's a really good boy in the house, a little excited about visitors and passerbys but responds well to correction. Naughty behaviors like countersurfing or begging are easily interrupted with a verbal no. No accidents or destructive behaviors. He would do amazing with a couple or family with older kids in a calm home that wants a companion animal. No cats or small kids. Balanced dogs considered.

Adoption Info:
Adoption fee is $400 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online: www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.FOSTER UPDATE: 12/28/20 Precious is a fantastic companion and a loyal dog. She loves to snuggle (and snore!) and when it is a bit colder she loves to snooze with you under a blanket. She is very playful and doing zoomies outside is one of her favorite pastimes. When you come back home she will wag her tail so hard that it almost hits her in her face. She continues to be a calm dog indoors and does perfectly when she is alone. We've done some time-lapses when we were out and she mainly snoozes on the sofa and stares at the squirrels in the garden. She is not a barky dog but will alert you by barking once when the doorbell is rung. She learns commands easily; in a matter of days, she learned to sit and stay when we put her food on the ground. We can even walk out of her sight without her running towards her bowl. She loves people but can be a bit nervous/protective when new people or dogs approach her. She usually does warm up to people quickly though. Due to a lack of socialization, she still needs to work on her dog reactiveness. At this time she should be the only dog in the home.

animal.description:
Miss Phoebe is one extremely friendly gal who happily accepts cuddles from absolutely everyone. She loves attention! Scratches and rubs are the key to her heart. The more adults, the merrier for Phoebe! As she does not like to be alone, her ideal home could include another dog to be her best friend, or a family so she can truly embrace all of the attention she craves and deserves from everyone. She does not do well around cats. In her spare time, she enjoys sleeping, being goofy and playing. Phoebe is so excited to find her furever home! 

Phoebe does need slow introductions to new dogs in a quiet atmosphere. She warms up to them, but if the atmosphere is too busy, she gets nervous and acts out. She does not like to be left alone and does take meds to help with her with her separation anxiety. She is on special food for kidney disease. She may be ten, but she's got a lot life left in her! She's good at doing stairs and does very well in the car! For her, a car ride is a great opportunity for a nap! She is super friendly dog who needs a furever home that has the patience for her to learn to trust and relax. She comes with her issues, but the cuddles, kisses and unconditional love she gives make it all worth while! 

Adoption Fee: $250
Location: Foster Home

animal.description:
Tazz A222216 

Tazz is a 3 year old neutered male who came into the shelter on 10/28/20 as an owner surrender.  

Treats 12/12: https://youtu.be/322zO--kUV8
More Play 11/28: https://youtu.be/4mYtrnGD9qA
Fetching 11/21: https://youtu.be/VzYLxZ2jMZc
Playing 11/14: https://youtu.be/3theD_9hsR8
Handling 11/14: https://youtu.be/lauRGA2RXY4
Handling video: https://youtu.be/exXtVbCM71I

Tazz has pizzazz!

He came in skinny and sad. Owner surrenders either shutdown right away or a few days in after being in the shelter sets in. Tazz definitely was still blissfully unaware when we had him out the first day. He was so happy to receive attention from people giving him yummy treats for just being himself. 

Tazz sits on command and allows all over handling. For being so skinny he is particular about what he puts in his body, no basic treats for this guy. When he wanted more treats he did the cutest butt scoot closer but not being too invasive in our personal space. Tazz wags his tail like he means it too. 

Tazz LOVES toys and is amazing at fetch.  He brings the ball back and drops on command.  He’s happy to self-entertain with toys and when you want some attention from him, he’s happy to let you rub his belly.

animal.description:
Nora A221589 

Nora is a 6 year old spayed female who came into the shelter on 10/6/20 as a confiscate.

Handling 12/15: https://youtu.be/orX1n9jPBCk
Handling 11/7: https://youtu.be/czotOVo5wFA
Handling: https://youtu.be/kjiGgpJl-zg

Look at that face!! Look at those eyes!! BEAUTIFUL!! She is so bewildered by the shelter environment. Not sure how she got here or why she is here. We have spent time with her over the past week since age arrived at the shelter and can see it will take a little more time for her to trust us. She is easy to leash up and take outside-she has learned the routine! When she sees the volunteer with treats and a leash approach her kennel she knows that mean it’s her turn and she is ready!! Outside she keeps to herself coming close enough to ask for more treats but staring deeply into your eyes and making quiet snort sounds-that means “I would like more treats please”. 

Nora spends most of her time sniffing the perimeter of the play yard and will often watch trucks as they park nearby-I imagine she is thinking to herself “are they here for me ?” She misses someone and seems quite well cared for. Soon we know she will trust us at the shelter and see we only want the best for her. Give her a few days and she will blossom!! We love her don’t you??

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: Winnie
*Age: 3 years
*Current Weight: 50 lbs
*Rescued from: Houston, Texas
*Adoption fee: $375 

Winnie was rescued from the streets of Houston, Texas, where she was struggling to keep her litter of babies alive. All of her babies found amazing homes through SNARR and now it is Winnie's turn. Winnie is extremely loyal and affectionate to her people. She is a very soulful dog. She has many other doggie friends in her foster home, but requires proper introductions to other dogs. She follows her people from room to room and is very affectionate, but requries a slow introduction to feel comfortable around strangers. She would make someone who spends a lot of time at home a perfect company and best friend. 

*Health: up to date on required vaccines

IMPORTANT: This dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a strictly-enforced signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Kai is a 7 month old shepherd mix and weighs around 35lbs, we expect him to be around 45-55lbs full grown. 

REQUIREMENTS FOR ADOPTION:
- Fully Fenced Yard
- Will commit to obedience training and ongoing human & people socialization
- Understands resource guarding and how to behaviorally redirect
- No cats, no dogs under 25lbs, or kids under the age of 8

Kai’s history isn’t fully known so he's been in a foster home being evaluated...Kai is highly intelligent, loves to snuggle, trains quickly and has some early resource guarding tendencies and prey drive that will require experience or training!  He’s potty trained, kennel trained, knows basic commands (sit, wait, heel and kennel) and walks well on a leash.

Kai can be possessive of his people and displays velcro dog tendencies - he’s a loyal boy and loves deeply therefore a family that is experienced with resource guarding or is willing to go through obedience training is a must.  

Kai is a medium energy pup who loves to go for long walks, enjoys obedience training and playing with his foster dog siblings!  He has some prey drive so no small animals - cats, dogs, birds, etc.  Kai is respectful of dogs his size or bigger, especially the female dogs.  

He is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, and microchipped. The adoption fee is $550; please submit an application via our website.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN BUFORD, PLEASE GO TO OUR WEBSITE TO READ ABOUT THE ADOPTION PROCESS AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION. www.furkidrescue.org 

Buford was found with another Beagle as a stray in Mississippi. He had an old break in his leg which could not be fixed, so it had to be amputated. He also had really bad teeth and had to have 13 of them pulled! He is approximately 8-10 years of age. 

Buford is pretty chill for the most part. He likes to sleep in his dog bed for most of the day, but if he hears a treat bag or food being eaten, he is wide awake and your best friend! He is only 20 pounds, and you will need to make sure that he does not over eat and become overweight, otherwise it will be very taxing with just three legs. We are hoping to find him a home with no stairs, or only a couple of stairs that the human is willing to carry him up and down if needed. He can do stairs, but this could be one an issue as he ages in a few years. 

He is currently fostered with a cat, but he does chase her. Your cat wound have to be the kind of cat that isn’t going to take his bullying! 

You will not be considered for Buford if you plan to use the tie out.

{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name:Skittles
Size: ~Medium range: 26-60 lbs
Adoption Donation:$200 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Spayed Female, Vaccinations current, Microchip, No other pets, No children, and must have a fenced-in yard.

Skittleswould luv to be your forever girl!

Foster Home Feedback

*
Skittles needs a home with No other pets, No children, and must have a fenced-in yard

1/3/21: Skittles has been really great, she loves to play but she can also be a very lazy dog that sleeps the day away. I do not kennel her when I am gone and she has not had any accidents or ruined anything! She has a stuffed carrot that she absolutely adores right now. She just gently nibbles on it and carries it around with her, it has a squeaker in it but she doesn't even play hard enough to make a peep. Skittles also absolutely loves playing fetch and she plays very nice when we do play, and is very good at dropping toys.

Skittles has been doing great meeting new people. She has had a couple of adoption meets, she stayed the weekend at another foster's home, she has even been going to the shelter to help me train in new volunteers! Skittles loves car rides and she rides really well in the car. Thank you for considering this sweet girl.

11/22/2020: Skittles has had a little more difficult path than most dogs have to take at her age. She contracted parvovirus at 5 weeks old so she did not get the socialization that most dogs get in the first year of their life. She can be nervous meeting new people. Skittles is getting more comfortable meeting and seeing people every day she spends with me though. I expect the improvements to continue. We are working hard on clicker training and keeping her attention, on walks or any time there is a curious noise outside.

Skittles is really great in the house. She spends the day snoozing or chewing on a bone, while I am at work and generally remains calm while I am home. She doesn't destroy anything when she is left alone. Skittles has had no accidents in the month or so that I have been fostering her. She will go into her kennel willingly but she would prefer to not be in there. We are working on making the kennel a positive space that she can go to and feel safe.

Skittles absolutely loves to go exploring and sniffing around on walks. She really loves to play fetch as well and she plays very nicely. She rides fantastically in the car. Skittles REALLY needs someone to continue her training to keep her comfortable.
To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
Two friendly and affectionate older sisters, Roxy and Sara, are seeking a caring and loving new owner. They are 10 year old lab mixes and weigh approximately 65 lbs. They would love to call your living room "home" to lounge around and snuggle! They have been together since they were puppies and are looking for a new home together after the passing of their previous owner. They are very friendly and love new people, unfortunately they do not do well with other pets. On a leash they love to go on walks and sit outside, and are very content to hang around with you as you complete the daily chores. Sara is in good all-around health, though Roxy is beginning to feel a little arthritic. They hope they go to a
home with someone home much of the time, as they do need frequent potty breaks. The sisters may not have as much energy as they did when they were puppies, but would still love to run and greet you when you come home. Give these sisters a chance to fill your home with happiness during their silver years.


Adult dog adoptions include - spay/neuter, vaccines, microchip, 4dx, fecal, and flea preventative.  

Puppy adoptions include - spay/neuter, vaccines including boosters, microchip, fecal,  and flea preventative 

Adoptions are held every Saturday from 10am-3pm at our shelter (1049 Macarthur Road in Whitehall across the street from the old Lehigh Valley Dairy) 

For more information please email us at dogs@lvpeaceablekingdom.info 

Applications can be downloaded at www.lvpeaceablekingdom.info

All adoptions must be completed in person - we are unable to ship or transport dogs.

animal.description:
CJ ~2 years old. Good with dogs. Kids and cats TBD. Needs a companion animal.

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC only

Hello world! My name is CJ. I am a sweet but very timid and shy girl that is looking for my forever home. I am a very pretty girl, and am about 1-2 years old. I have a slender build. I weigh about 60 pounds, and won't get much bigger.

Not much is known about my past. I ended up in a small rural shelter. I was so scared that I would not even let anyone near me. The volunteers worked on gaining my trust, and I was able to get into the rescue. I am going to need a special home. I am extremely fearful of new people and new things. Once I learn to trust you, I am totally devoted, and act like a typical happy dog. i know, I know, it sounds like a tale of two extremes...and it basically is.

I am very bonded to my foster mom. She saved me from the scary shelter, feeds me every day, and has earned my trust. I act like a very enthusiastic and silly dog when she is around. I will run around the yard wagging my tail and jumping around. I also try to jump on my foster mom for attention. Occasionally I get to sleep in the bed and I think this is a great treat. I need some manners and need to learn to curb my enthusiasm. I do need some work on leash walking. We have not done that yet because I have been going through heartworm treatment, and had to stay quiet and stress free.

When I am not with my foster mom, I am a lot more reserved around other people. I get easily frightened by new and unfamiliar things/environments. I am terrified of the vets office.... I will need a patient owner who is willing to spend time with me to continue to expose me to new things and help desensitize me. I have a lot of potential.

I do like other dogs. I do better with middle aged dogs...ones who will play with me and yet not be too wild and crazy. I am learning a LOT from my furry foster friend Jazz. She is an old timer, and she is my best buddy. I look to her for guidance. I am much more confident dog when she is around. Foster mom says I need to have an medium to large doggie companion in my next home to help me continue to gain confidence and learn appropriate behaviors. I will also require a nice yard with privacy fence. I am not a candidate for leash walking...I need a yard to run around and let out my energy.

I am crate trained and thrive on structure. I really am a diamond in the rough. I am looking forward to finding a new family that sees my potential and will help me become an even better dog. I promise you years of adventures and love.

Come and meet me soon! I look forward to meeting you!

For more information on our adoptable pet list please visit: Adoptable Pet List

animal.description:
Lilly is a Bully-Breed mix who is extremely intelligent and has a giant heart.  She has some special needs that can be addressed with patience, routine and commitment.  Once you meet her, you’ll fall in love with those warm eyes.  

She is 5 years old, about 50 pounds, UTD on vaccines, microchipped, in good health, spayed, housebroken and has such a classy lookin’ black and white coat.

Her body language communicates her desire to bond and clearly indicates if she’s feeling uneasy.  So much of the world is new to Lilly.  Her past included very little social time; many sounds and situations are new to her.

Throughout her year with Lucky Paws Rescue, she has put her right paw forward in all endeavors.  Her confidence has grown ten-fold.  She is a true companion dog.

Lilly can be shy and sometimes on edge when experiencing new social situations and sounds.  She’s done an impressive job of working through her hesitancies.  With the support of professional dog trainers, Lilly has conquered many new life chapters.  She now realizes trucks make loud noises but will not harm her and she has developed wonderful leash skills when walking through the neighborhood and even retail stores.

The Cedar River Dog Farm training team have found Lilly loves intermittent down-times.  She adores being wrapped in a cozy blanket, likes to hang out in open-door crate and feels more confident when wearing a weighted vest.

Given some transition time, Lilly is a true cuddler!  She’s been known to climb right into your lap, take a nap near your feet and, if invited, will lay in bed by your side.

Lilly is looking for a low-key home with a fenced yard, sorry no kids or cats.  A very balanced family dog may offer her a great partnership.  Lilly’s first choice is to be the only dog so she can soak up all the love. 

Lilly loves physical activity and relishes opportunities for agility play.  She has impressive dexterity skills, loves jumping on large tree stumps, hurdles, ramps, bridges and even climbing a ladder!   

Lilly needs a new foster or forever home before Valentine’s Day.  Trainer support will continue when she moves to her new environment.

If you are interested in Lily, please copy/paste the link below into your internet browser to fill out our application:

http://form.jotform.us/form/50488470409157

animal.description:
This big hunk is Wynston! He is a 7(ish) year old American Bulldog who was surrendered to a shelter after his owner's lost their home. He is completely ready to move in your house and steal not just your heart, but also your bed!

Wynston is a very smart dog and currently knows sit, shake, off, leave it, kennel, and come. In typical bully fashion he has a wiggly wiggly behind and needs time to adjust to a new environment. 

Wynston does well with other dogs but does need a proper introduction, same with cats! At first glance we thought there was no way he could live with cats, but after he learned they weren't fun toys to chase, he co exists just fine. This guy does need a fenced yard!

This big boy is everything you could want. Smooshy and cuddly, energetic and playful, goofy and entertaining! Wynston is one of our longer dog residents here and we would love to see him finally get into his furever home. 

Wynston is UTD on shots, preventative, micro-chipped, and neutered!

Wynston’s adoption fee is $250, and adopters must live within 175 miles of the Quad City Area.

If interested in meeting Wynstonyou must fill out the online application at www.k9kindnessrescue.org/adopt/application

Wynston and K9 Kindness Rescue thank you for considering adoption

animal.description:
CAPTAIN ~9-10 years old. Good with kids and dogs. Good with seniors/elderly. Apartment appropriate. Cats TBD.

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC only

Hello, my name is Captain and my foster Mom says I am a perfect older gentleman. I was found tied to a tree with a large metal chain, now I know that sounds sad but that has not made me dislike people. I love everyone I meet. Especially if they have treats or a ball. I do not like to be crated. and unfortunately my foster parents learned that the hard way when I broke the door off. I just really enjoy sleeping on a comfy floor and being near. my people. I would do best in a house or an apartment with NO stairs. Being an older distinguished gentleman stairs are a bit tough because of my arthritis and hips. I still love to go on walks but no hiking or jogging. I do get along with my foster fur-sister but do not really sure how to play right now. I would love to be the only dog in the house so you can spoil me rotten in my golden days. I do not have the best house manners right now because it is all new to me. So don't be mad if I go into an open pantry and try to help myself! No worries, I do correct easily with a firm NO!.

If you want someone to make you their world I am totally your guy. Don't let my age fool you. I am young at heart and I've got a ton of love left to give!

PLEASE NOTE: Captain will not be placed in an adoptive home until medically cleared as we are addressing some ear issues and will be seeing a specialist. After that he will need to go thru heartworm treatment.For more information on our adoptable pet list please visit: Adoptable Pet List

animal.description:
Gracie is located in TEXAS. There are not enough homes for all the unwanted dogs down there, so she is willing to relocate for a good, loving, forever home.

Gracie was saved from a fast kill, small-town dog pound. She is a Blue Lacy Mix, 3-1/2 years old and weighing 40 pounds. She has the distinctive Lacy bark. We discovered that she had already been spayed and had a microchip (the pound did not scan her).  The contact for her microchip had "rehomed" her, and that person never updated the chip. Her original owner says that she had to rehome Gracie because she was growling at the kids. We think the kids were probably giving her a reason to growl at them. Regardless, Gracie is probably not a good fit for homes with very young children. Gracie is housetrained, crate trained, and knows how to sit. She tolerates well-mannered dogs but is an alpha and will put annoying ones in their place. She would probably do best paired with a male dog that respects her space. Gracie likes to run and explore and will play a bit with other dogs. She is very food motivated and loves to eat. Her portions must be monitored. She guards her food and treats from other dogs, so food must be kept separate.  When we got her, Gracie was missing fur on her butt and tail area. This was flea bite Dermatitis. We gave her a flea pill and her fur is now completely grown back.  It would be best if potential adopters were familiar with the breed. Gracie must be in the house as a loved member of the family. She must have a securely fenced yard to run and play.

Gracie is healthy. She is spayed, fully vaccinated, and microchipped. She is negative for heartworms and on monthly heartworm and flea preventative. Gracie has a  $500.00 adoption fee that includes transport to Brewster NY, Nanuet NY, or Rocky Hill CT. She is being fostered in Texas and will not be sent north until after she is adopted. Please email  2 Many Dogs Rescue for an adoption application if you are interested in adopting this pretty girl. If you are on Facebook, PLEASE visit and LIKE our page: www.facebook.com/2ManyDogsRescue

Shanook is approximately 13 yrs old
Neutered, UTD and hw negative
Doesn't mind cats 
Ok with female dogs and small dogs.  
Tends to be aggressive towards male dogs.
Would be fine as an only dog
Good on a leash
Good manners about food.

He is older and has some quirks.  His ideal home would be with someone who is home to spend time with him.  A physically fenced in yard for him to explore and a couch to crash on and a doggy door to allow him indoor and outdoor access.  He's still the absolute sweetest and deserves to live his final years feeling loved and adored, something he has lacked most of his life.  If you just want a companion dog, this is your guy!

His adoption fee is sponsored for the right family, but you still have to go through our adoption process.  Shanook is located in middle TN.  You must fill out our adoption application form to be considered.  It is on our website at www.safehaventn.com and we are happy to arrange a meet and greet once your application has been approved.

animal.description: Madre #7188 is a 3-year-old female Shepherd mix. She is a friendly and outgoing lady. She absolutely loves people and will jump up to meet you. For this reason, she should be in a home without young children as she might accidentally jump on them in her excitement. Madre is good with other dogs. She is crate trained and also responds to the “sit” command. She is extremely treat-motivated; this will be a great way to work on her training. She does tend to pull a bit on the leash because she is so excited to explore. Madre is extremely high-energy and will need an outlet for plenty of exercise or a fenced-in backyard. She came to us with puppies and heartworms. Now she is ready for some much-needed R&R and a family who will continue LCAR’s provided Heartworm treatment at no cost. She weighs 60 pounds and is full grown. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
Scar is about 1.5 years old. He is a very sweet, affectionate and driven boy. He is learning quickly and is doing well at his foster home. He gets along well with dogs but has high prey drive, so cats are for chasing, not living with. Scar would do great in a home that can give him plenty of exercise and mental stimulation. He could do well at any dog sport. He's gentle with his teeth and does great with kids. 

Scar's foster dad says that he eats a lot and plays even more! Scar is incredibly excited to greet him every day. He follows family members around throughout the day. In true Mal fashion, Scar is very intelligent. He's attentive to his handler, and does almost everything he's asked to do; sit, lay, down, up... He is crate trained and sleeps throughout the night. No accidents. He does get the happy pees when he gets super excited, so his foster has been working on this with him by having him calm down before giving him any attention (as best you can with a Mal). Did we mention that he is great with other dogs? :o)

He is a little protective over his bone, but not aggressive. He just doesn't want to share. Scar is a young dog with lots of potential who will excel in just about anything!

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog.

animal.description:
Sheyla is 4.5 years old. She lives with her foster in California (mid-state). She is UTD on all shots. Shes very sweet, food motivated and smart. She has good recall, sits and lies down on command. She will need some help with loose-leash walking. She scales fences so needs a safe enclosure. She likes being around her humans. She likes to chase anything fast so she needs an experienced handler who can help her reach her full potential!

She might be good at agility or FastCAT!

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

Introducing, Krispy Kreme Rat Terrier. His mature adult owner moved in with her family who has children and Krispy was not happy. He is not good with children or cats. He.needs a calm adult home with a regular schedule and time to spend with him. He is loving and gives kisses once he trusts you and he will let you know when he needs to go potty. The vet said he is blind in one eye possibly from head trauma Krispy can see with the other eye and doesn't walk into anything, we address him from his sited side so he knows we are approaching him for cuddles. We do feel he would be best as an only dog so he can get all the loving. He will be getting a dental cleaning and then ready for his home. He is 8-9 years old. and 13 pounds. He is small and muscular. A FAB walking buddy! Krispy's adoption fee is $300 to go towards his vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, and microchip as well as grooming if needed). If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. 

 *All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. * All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health.*All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

Dogs: $155
Cats: $95
Puppies under 4 months: $115 plus S/N Deposit: $100
Kittens under 4 months: $70 plus S/N Deposit: $100

All pets available for adoption have been spayed or neutered (unless under 4 months please read about our adoptions
here
), are current on vaccinations and preventatives, and micro-chipped. Cats have been tested and confirmed negative for Feline AIDS and Leukemia. Dogs have been tested for heartworm disease.

Our shelter is located at 42 Deep River Rd in Sanford and is open Tues, Thurs, & Fri from 3pm - 7pm & Sat from 10-2pm (other times available by appointment). CARA's adoption process and online application can be found at
http://www.cara-nc.org/info/adoption

If you would like to adopt me or any of my friends, please visit CARA to fill out an on-line application or e-mail us at adoptions@cara-nc.org.

Every animal that comes into the CARA program is here because one or more events occurred that led to this animal needing not only a home, but a person or family to love and protect them. Each animal has been loved and cared for by a small and determined group of people who want nothing more than to know each animal is safe for the rest of his or her life. Thank you for looking to adopt!

animal.description:
Austin has had a rough start to 2020 and is looking for humans who will make a much brighter future. He is a 31.2 pound tall and lanky boy with tons of energy to run off! Austin is a 1 year old Vizla mix who needs a home with a strong leader who is
committed
to working with and training him. He had previously been adopted from another rescue but soon found himself escaping out of his home and wandering the streets. Luckily HARTT (Humane Animal Rescue Trapping Team) got involved and was able to successfully trap him. Austin was found in a storm gutter fearing humans and needing to relearn how to trust. Sadly his adopters no longer wanted Austin and we had the pleasure of taking in this goofy boy. He loves to play with other dogs of all sizes but does need a proper introduction first, so any other dogs in the home will need to meet him prior to adoption. He can become possessive of his people towards other dogs but responds well to verbal corrections, so he will need ongoing work with that if there are other dogs in his home. Austin is very shy and will need time and patience to make friends with humans. He prefers women to men, so he may take more time to warm up to any men in the home. He is looking for a home with only adults and older teens as children spook him. Austin has done well with cats but will try to play with them, so would do best with confident, dog savvy cats. He is getting better on the leash each time he goes out but will need additional training as he adjusts in his forever home. Austin will need a vigilant home that will keep Austin safe and off the streets. He is kennel trained, but will need ongoing work on his potty training. No apartments or rentals with breed or weight restrictions. He is neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped and vet checked. His adoption fee of $160 includes a free vet visit. To potentially adopt Austin,

please fill out an application (found here: https://azsmalldog.org/adoption-forms/) and send to

fosterdogboots@gmail.com

animal.description:
MILLIE: 18 months old, 38lbs (As of 12/15), Boxer Mix, Spayed Female, Medium to Higher Active 

She goes from 0 to 100 in the blink of an awestruck eye. Her movements are tight. Shes a muscular little machine built for whip like romping, and she needs a playmate who can keep her on her toes. Millie is 18 months old, only 38 lbs, and shes got nipples for days. This boxer/beagle mix has clearly been used as a puppy machine her entire short life, so now that shes got a chance to be an independent woman, her engine is revving with youthful energy. She wants to frolic, rumble, pounce, and dash then flop over for belly rubs and cuddles. Shes fueled by sweetness, very treat motivated, and learns fast. Shell need plenty of exercise and some basic training to keep her adult dog manners on the right track, and shes super responsive to direction so shell make a star student. Millie could also use some socialization work with other dogs her size and bigger, sometimes they bug her out and she doesnt know how to say hello politely. Shell shine in an active experienced home, older kids or grownups only since shes a little clumsy and might accidentally hurt someone small.

Her foster mom says: Millie is doing great! We've worked up to a good amount of time in the crate, and she's doing amazing with it. I'm also working on sit, stay, and no mouthing while playing commands. She's making some progress! She literally rolls over and demands a belly rub every time she sees any of my doormen, so we're also working on that too. Sometimes it makes for an awkward moment when they don't want to pet or they're busy, but it's SO cute most people can't resist. :) Also, she would be amazing for a family that loves to sleep in this pup will happily sleep in until 9 or 10 and be okay waiting to use the bathroom. I've never met a dog that sleeps so late! Interested in adopting? Submit an application at socialteesnyc.org or email your point person if youve already been approved!

PLEASE NOTE: This animal is not at the Social Tees office all of our dogs and cats are in foster homes while they wait to find their forever families. :) If youd like to apply to adopt this pet, please complete an adoption application at socialteesnyc.org. Because we are a small team and receive hundreds of applications each week, we are unable to respond to every application and every inquiry email, but we do our best. Please have patience! If your application is approved, you will for sure hear from us. If you have questions, please take a look at the Adoption and Fostering FAQs etc. on our website as all common questions are answered there. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility as we work to save these innocent lives!! 

LEARN MORE ABOUT US: socialteesnyc.org; Instagram via @socialteesnyc; Facebook.com/socialteesanimalrescue

animal.description:
Are you looking for the love of your life, who will give you all of his attention? The sweetest boy, who uses a wheelchair to get around, and is working so hard to gain mobility back in his hind legs? Well, then Thurmond is your guy. Thurmond so sweet and needs a family that is able to help him get around and give him lots of attention. He would prefer a home without toddler age children who may try grab him. Thurmond's perfect day would be spending time outside in the wheelchair to explore the yard and find sticks to chew on, laying in the sun and then enjoying some couch life, snuggles and attention. Thurmond is ready to be your best friend. He loves other dogs and all people.

Age: 6-years-old

Breed: Lab Mix

Weight: 53 lbs

Kid-friendly: Unknown (older considerate kids should be OK)

Dogs: Yes! Being fostered with 2 other dogs

Cats: Likes to chase cats, so probably not

Crate trained: Thurmond does not like being crated, but he's a great guy and doesn't get into anything. He can't jump so he can't get on furniture and as long as he has a blanket that's where he hangs out.

Potty trained: Yes, with exceptions. While there have not been accidents when the fosters were away from the home, there have been a few times he wasn't able to hold it while the fosters were getting him ready to go out/ they weren't quick enough. Thurmond will tell you he needs to go out by licking your hands, but ultimately he does his poops immediately after his meals.

Health concerns: His back legs currently don't work too well, so he uses a wheelchair to get around. We have seen progress and do hope he'll regain full strength in his back legs. As of right now he had open wounds that came from him dragging his legs that we have had to tend to, we're almost all healed up but still require bandaging and will most likely need to wear protective boots or socks once he is fully healed to prevent more injury. He is heart worm positive and in the process of completing his treatment.

Adoption fee: $325

Our dogs receive heartworm and flea/tick prevention the first week of each month, March through November. Dogs that have stage 3 or 4 dental disease will receive a dental procedure in rescue. We aspirate all lumps and remove those that our veterinary partners suggest removing.

Adopters will be responsible for continued preventatives, follow-up appointments, and medications (if applicable).

$50 discount for seniors (65+) and veterans. Adoption fees help pay for the dog's veterinary exam, vaccinations (rabies, distemper, and bordetella), HW test, blood panel, a microchip, and spay/neuter if needed and additional health needs specific to each animal.

You can apply to adopt at www.greyfacerescue.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
***FENCED IN YARD REQUIRED***

Meet Merlin - is a 13 month old harlequin who is the definition of momma’s boy. He doesn’t have a mean bone in him, he’s super affectionate and will Velcro to his momma. He loves to cuddle and will be very loyal to her forever person. 

Merlin is currently living in a foster care with two toy breed dogs, two cats, and older kids - and she’s great with all but would really do best in a household with another large breed canine playmate to run and play with. 
He loves to play with the other dogs so has frequent dog play date sessions.

He can be timid at first with new people, but warms up quickly. Especially if there are treats involved!! He is so super food motivated!

Merlin is 100% puppy and craves constant attention. Prior to coming into rescue he lived outside with his sister, stormy, for the first year of his life. He has no formal training and will need a patient family to show him the way. The two biggest things his foster family is currently working on with him are potty training and not jumping on everyone. He loves treats so it’s a good motivation for him to learn. 

when we first got him in, he was terrified of being on a leash and collar. We have been working to desensitize him and make walking on leash a fun activity and he’s doing so much better.

Merlin has been fully vaccinated, neutered, and micro chipped.

To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Merlin, please go to: www.nwflgdr.com/adopt. 

Merlin‘s adoption fee is $400.

ATTENTION: If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Millie is one of our dogs that has been through a lot. Previous to her Grey Face rescue, Millie had been severely neglected, which led to untreated dental abscesses that became so severe, that they created open and painful wounds in her face. Because of Millie's neglect, it takes her some time to develop trust with new humans. Millie's perfect adopter would be patient and kind, and have a quiet home. They would allow her to acclimate slowly, and give her lots of bacon and love.

Once you have gained Millie's trust, she is a very sweet and low maintenance dog. She really loves being pet, including ear and butt scratches. Millie also loves walks, and sniffing around, and did we mention bacon? She is perfectly potty-trained and does well left out to explore during the day. She is a pretty quiet dog, but she will let you know if a stranger or other dog is outside. She has the cutest little "awoo" whenever she is left alone, just so you don't forget about her. Millie is very unsure of other dogs and cats. Her initial reaction is to growl and keep them as far away from her as possible. We are recommending a home without other pets.

Age: 7-years-old

Breed: Shar-Pei Mix

Weight: 34 lbs

Kid-friendly: Potentially, after very long and slow introductions (older, respectful children)

Dogs: No animals in adopter's home is highly recommended

Cats: No animals in adopter's home is highly recommended

Crate trained: Not kenneled in foster home, but can be trusted to be left out during the day

Potty trained: Absolutely! Can hold it for 10-11 hours

Likes: Food! Millie loves human food of any kind, Greenies, Milkbones, bacon, etc. She only seems to enjoy toys that have food inside of them. Very much likes human attention, walks, and sniffing.

Health concerns: HW+, open wounds on face that are healing - need to be cleaned daily

Adoption fee: $325

Our dogs receive heartworm and flea/tick prevention the first week of each month, March through November. Dogs that have stage 3 or 4 dental disease will receive a dental procedure in rescue. We aspirate all lumps and remove those that our veterinary partners suggest removing.

Adopters will be responsible for continued preventatives, follow-up appointments, and medications (if applicable).

$50 discount for seniors (65+) and veterans. Adoption fees help pay for the dog's veterinary exam, vaccinations (rabies, distemper, and bordetella), HW test, blood panel, a microchip, and spay/neuter if needed and additional health needs specific to each animal.

You can apply to adopt at www.greyfacerescue.org/adoption-application

Sunflower is very quiet and sweet with a lot of tail wags!  Sunflower is interested in her surroundings, and is learning about toys and how to play.  She loves her soft and cuddly bed and was so excited to have one of her very own!  Sunflower is fully vaccinated, microchipped, current on vaccinations, fecal testing, and dvm exam.  She is not a good fit for cats, and she does best with children over 13 years old and with calmer dogs in the household.  

Sunflower came to us all the way from Thailand in partnership with SOI Dog Foundation.  Sunflower was a victim of a cruelty case....here is some more information about her when was was in Thailand:
"Beautiful Sunflower was found in a world of unbearable suffering after someone slashed her across the head and body. It was a deliberate, savage attack on a defenseless dog.  The wounds were seriously infected and over time, they became infested with maggots. She was in so much pain. It took months of medical treatment and tender loving care to heal not just her physical wounds, but her fear and confusion. Thankfully, she recovered and has now, all thanks to generous animal lovers like you, left the Soi Dog shelter for her new life overseas." 

Sunflower is available for adoption through WPFC.  Please submit an adoption application if you are interested in her.  She will have a few additional adoption requirements as a SOI Dog adoption partner- we will provide that information to potential adoption applicants.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Quieter children over 13 years old are okay for Sunflower.  She is also okay with some (older, dog-savvy) cats and quieter dogs.  She can be dog selective.

animal.description:
Meet Chauncey, a 6 y/o, 95 lb, Great Pyrenees who is looking for his forever home.  Chauncey is pretty laid back, enjoys a nice walk,  and will also be happy to binge watch Netflix with you.  Chauncey is ok with other dogs as long as they are not in your face since Chauncey is more interested in chilling and not playing.  Chauncey needs a cat free home and a fenced in yard.  
If you feel he may be a good match please fill out the application in comments!

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
Meet Clifford!

Clifford is almost a year old and has had a rough first year of life! Clifford was born and lived on the streets of Houston where he experienced no kindness from humans, so he became very fearful of them and evaded trapping for quiet sometime. He eventually was trapped due to becoming paralyzed from a tick-borne illness, after receiving treatment that cured his paralysis in Houston, he made his way to the PNW where we know there is a perfect family willing to give this boy a second chance at life!

Clifford’s perfect home would consist of:

•	An older mentor dog, Clifford needs a mentor dog to help teach him how to be a dog. He needs to help teach him to trust humans and help him build his confidence.
•	Daily walks, Clifford is just learning to be on leash and is doing amazing. He has great leash skills and once you get his lead on he is ready to go. The walks have helped him build confidence and bond with his pack.
•	Lots of toys! He loves playing with toys and it helps keep his destructive puppy ways at bay.
•	Structure with crate training, Clifford needs a space to feel safe and a spot he can be when his hoomans are not around or unable to watch him.
•	He would love to have kids in his home! He warms up much quicker to kiddos and has loved all the ones he has met so far!
•	A fenced yard to play with his pack in!
•	Someone with patience, Clifford has come SO SO far but will still take time to warm up. It may take him a couple of weeks to begin trusting his new environment and people, so someone who is able to give him the time and space to come to them will be a must! 

Clifford just needs to be treated like a dog. No special treatment or babying. He has had a hard life but just needs a patient and consistent human, a mentor dog or two and time to open up! He is such a sweet guy and we know the perfect home is out there for him!

**Clifford will only be adopted to a home with other dogs and a fenced yard, so that he can continue to grow and thrive!**


PLEASE READ COMPLETELY 

All of our kids are being raised in volunteer foster homes, so we do not have a single location to visit. You will need to submit an application to be approved for a Meet and Greet.

If you are interested in adopting or more information please do the following before contacting Path of Hope: 

1. Go to our website www.pathofhoperescue.com 
2. Thoroughly read through the FAQ section on the "Adopt" page (this will answer most questions!)
3. If you are still interested, fill out an online application on our website and our Matchmaker will be in touch with you! 
4. Follow us on facebook, https://www.facebook.com/pathofhoperescue/ , to see lots of cute puppy photos. learn about puppy events, and get updates on the rescue!

Our adoption fee for puppies is $400 and includes age appropriate core vaccines, minimum two rounds of dewormer, microchip with free registration and spay/neuter surgery. A refund of $100 is available with completion of any training class.

animal.description:
Skye is a high energy Catahoula Leopard Dog, and true to her breed, she loves to work and can get into a bit of trouble if left to her own devices for too long.  She is a double merle and deaf, and as a result is quite vocal - she doesn't realize how loud she can be! Her barks can be alarming to others at first, so slow and distant first introductions are necessary. Skye understands basic sign commands and does well with a routine. 

Skye is a very active dog who needs plenty of exercise and mental stimulation every single day. Her current routine involves 10-12km spread out into a few walks and sometimes trips to the forest where she enjoys off leash time. She also loves to run, retrieve and play. Skye gets along with some dogs, often preferring large male dogs to medium-small dogs or females. Skye suffers from separation anxiety, and along with her daily exercise and mental stimulation, she takes anti-anxiety medication which has changed her life so much for the better! 

Though this diva asks a lot of her guardian, she will reward you by acting like a 10lb lap dog and nuzzling up to you on the couch to watch a movie, she'll sleep with you too, but is also kennel trained. Skye is a loyal dog, she loves her people. She's great with older kids who can handle her high energy and bounciness. 
 
Skye is looking for the right person or family who will continue to work with her to help her be her best doggo!  She needs an active home with someone who is determined to keep up with her reward based fear free training and have patience with her. Dog experience required, breed experience a definite asset. 
 
If you're interested in adopting Skye, please apply! To do so click on the 'More about Us' button, then click the link to apply and scroll to the bottom of the page where it says Adoption application: Dog. 

*no cats
*no young children
*no small dogs

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Large male maybe okay, Skye gets jealous.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.If interested in any of our animals for adoption, or to foster an animal, please fill out the respective application here to get the process started. Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.
Hi my name is Puppy! I know that sounds like a silly name but its been my name for 8 years. I came with my daddy Chico when my owner was no longer able to care for me. We were pretty scared for a few days but we really like our foster home. We have a large yard to explore and other dogs to play with if we choose. I always choose a lap! That is my favorite place. If one lap is not available I will choose another. I love people and seem to enjoy attention from children also. I am learning to play with a few toys and also enjoy a game of chase. The big dogs at my foster home are okay as long as they don't invade my space. I am working on potty training and am doing much better if you watch my cues. I really want a special forever home with warm laps and my daddy Chico. I missed him terribly when he was ill in the hospital. I will be ready for adoption when Chico is all set. I will be available in January after my spay.Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

An adult only home or a home with older kiddos would be best. I would love a dog pal but that would be dependent on a meet and greet here at the shelter. Ready for some high-IQ love? 

To enable us to hold Ashton for a meet and greet with you, a $25.00 deposit will be taken at the time you make an appointment. Your deposit will be credited toward your adoption if you choose to adopt, or refunded after your meet and greet if you decide that this pet is not a good match for you. Deposits will not be refunded if you cancel less than twenty-four hours before your appointment time.

animal.description:
**SERIOUS APPLICATIONS VIA WEBSITE ONLY. PHONE CALLS AND EMAILS WILL NOT BE RETURNED IN TIMELY MANNER**

www.barkmn.org

Applicants who have contact in-home or frequent contact with children will be denied. No exceptions. 

Brewster is a 5 yr old, 7.5lb male Chihuahua with a few trust issues. He has fear aggression and mild resource guarding (growls at other dogs if they get close to "his" stuff) type of issues. He was going to be euthanized for this behavior at the shelter but he has made a lot of progress in his foster home and is really coming out of his shell! He will need a very specific forever home with a very calm, confident person who can continue making progress with him. He is starting to show his personality, inviting dogs into play, and enjoys attention from his person! 


Brewster’s perfect person: 

-Does not live in a home with walls shared with neighbors. Brewster will alert bark to any voices and is terrified of strangers. 

-Does not have other animals. He is currently housed with other dogs and is slowly learning to “play” but he is pretty controlling while “playing” and can turn growl/snap at another dog if they’re too rough or get near “his” things. He’s a very vocal player also which seems to confuse some dogs. Essentially, his dog to dog communication skills need practice. The cat makes him very angry but he will tolerate their presence if need be. He tolerates other dogs but does not often seek out their company. He’s perfectly ok being a loner! 

-Someone who has a solid foundation and understanding of dog behavior and who is committed to ongoing training and treating Brewster like a DOG.  

- Someone who understands what  it means to own a dog like Brewster. He can never be left alone with children. Luckily he loves being in his crate and kennels easily upon command. He would do best with only one or two adults in the house. 

- A fenced yard. He has recently been allowed off leash to potty and he discovered zoomies are fun! He would love a safe place to run around! He will startle when he hears someone outside the fence and will attempt to run back inside or posture/bark at them. 

- Someone PATIENT. He did try to food-strike and not eat when stressed, initially, but he now knows that if he runs to his kennel like the other dogs and sits, he will receive his meals. He understands that he has to work for his meals or other desirable rewards and understands a few other “mannerly” dog things like sitting before allowed out of his kennel and walking nicely on the leash . His foster mom can easily pick him up, trim a nail or two, hand feed him, go for long walks (he LOVES walks) but it does take a while to get there with him. He has never offered to bite his foster family and now tries to beg for attention by climbing the baby gates to be near them.  

Brewster is kennel trained and easily crates for a work day. He happily greets his familiar people when they get home. He gains confidence in himself and his environment daily so we’re looking for the perfect person who can give him the safest forever home possible! 

Adoption fee negotiable to the right home.
