animal.description:
This is Baxter!

Baxter was found as a stray and taken to OC Shelter. As a blind dog, we can only imagine how scared he must have been! Baxter is 13 years old and weighs 22 lbs. Volunteers have taken him on a few outings and report he's a little nervous in the car, but once he's out, he's a happy boy!

One of our regular volunteers took Baxter on a two week Frosted Fling so we could learn how he does in a home environment. The answer is: Baxter is the best boy! His Fling Mom reports Baxter is potty trained and sleeps in a crate at night with no accidents. The only time he makes any noise is in the morning when he needs to go out, and he lets out a funny little howl. Baxter is a good eater who enjoys going for walks, napping in the sun, and cuddling. Baxter gets along great with his lab fling brother. Be sure to watch the video to see Baxter finding his way around in his Fling home and going for a walk. Being blind doesn't keep him from getting around inside or on walks!

Baxter's Fling Mom shared, "Baxter is the cutest little darling boy, and his face simply melts your heart. Baxter is so well-behaved. He is sleeping now after enjoying the beautiful sunset and getting exercise walking laps in the yard. His perfect forever family will feed him lots of food because he loves to eat, that look and head tilt when he smells food makes you laugh. He will enjoy short walkies during the day, kisses on his head and a warm comfy place where he will sleep through the night. He's the best boy and very, very quiet! He and his big lab fling brother have gotten along super from day one."

Baxter is ready to be a wonderful addition to your family! Apply to meet him: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/31/21 KG

animal.description:
Skarlet had an elderly owner who passed away. Her family could not care for her. She was very overweight and matted. We have her in a foster home where she has already lost ten pounds. Skarlett is eight years old and has some health issues. Our medical staff examined her and discovered she has Cushings disease. She had a dental cleaning and had lots of teeth pulled. She also has limited vision and cannot hear. 
Despite all of this, she is a friendly dog. She is not a lap dog but does like to sit next to her person. She is fine around other animals who do not pester her. Same with kids - if they are respectful with her, she is happy. She is kinda slow because of her weight and health issues. 
Skarlet is on twice daily tablets for the Cushings and twice daily eye drops for dry eye. The meds make her hungry all the time, but she is on weight maintenance food. She needs to be taken outside frequently - every two to three hours or she may go inside - not because she wants to. 
Skarlet will do best in a home where here person or people will be home most of the time. She's a real sweety!
Skarlet is on our medical None Left Behind program and her medicine for Cushings disease will be covered by the League. To make an appointment to meet Skarlet, call the shelter at 513-735-2299.

animal.description:
Hey there, I’m Scrappy and my name says it all!  I’m a 6-year old terrier mix, weighing about 50 pounds and I’m an active dog with lots of energy.  Before I was placed in a loving foster home, my former owner left me in the backyard all day long.  That was so darn boring and lonely.  I love people!  I love to be cuddled and walked and generally paid attention to—I’m trying to make up for all the time I spent alone in that backyard.

Because I’ve got a lot of energy, it’s important for me to find a home with a fenced-in yard.  I’m pretty chill around cats, and I might get along with another dog as long as it’s patient and can tolerate my high energy level.  Kids ages 8+ would probably get along just great with me!

Please consider me!  I promise that I will love you unconditionally for the rest of my life.

If you would like to adopt me, please reach out to Safe Paws Rescue and they will send you an application to begin the adoption process. Safe Paws is a small rescue, so they accept inquiries from residents in Pinellas County only, please.

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE: Remi has an application in process and is pending adoption!
Applications are reviewed in the order they are received. If you are waiting for a response, please understand that due to the volume of interest, replies may be delayed. Thank you for understanding! 

Remi is a 10 Month old, male German Shepherd/Husky mix.

Remi was surrendered to our southern rescue partner due to divorce, and they did not have time for him any more. Remi is very timid when he first meets a new person.  He is great with other dogs and it really brings him out of his shell to be around other dogs, though he might be a little much for small dogs.  
He walks well on leash and is also completely house trained.   

Remi needs a secure fenced yard if he is ever off leash, at least right now. He is easily startled and may bolt if a stranger tries to approach him if not in a secure fenced area when off leash.  He is also used to being in a crate. He is a very sweet dog, once he gets to know you and trust you, which doesn't take very long at all.  He is still a baby, and is easily trainable.  Remi is used to being around kids.  He hasn't been tested with cats.  He probably shouldn't live with cats, as most shepherds don't do well with them.

animal.description:
**Please read Mia's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

Meet Mia - a 2 year old, 55 pound, Plott Hound mix gal.

Mia’s fosters describe her as:
“The best snuggler and kiss giver! She is goofy and so affectionate!”
Check out her Instagram! @miagreatdogrescue

Mia is looking for a very special family! Mia is an active girl who loves to run and play fetch. She needs a quiet neighborhood to walk in and has been working on leash walking! Her new harness has helped a lot! Mia is a rough player with other dogs so we suggest she is the only dog in the home. She is not aggressive with other dogs so we think she will do fine with play dates - she just prefers to get all your attention. She also should not live with cats. She rides well in the car. She loves to bark to say hello! She gets so excited her entire butt wiggles!!! She is a lover and enjoys giving everyone kisses! She is great with little kids - very patient and affectionate with little ones and happy to run and play with bigger kids. She is housebroken but does not need her crate at all, knows ‘sit’ & ‘wait’ and that ‘go nunnites’ means to go to her dog bed in the bedroom to go to bed for the night. She will bark for a moment at guests when they come over but she stops once they can meet and people really love her. 

Mia is epileptic and is on a few daily medications. She has an emergency med for the 24 hours after she has a seizure. She recently started a new medication that has helped decrease her seizures. She will need to see a vet every 6 months to take blood to make sure her blood levels are okay on her current meds. She already has a vet neurologist and will continue care with this vet after adoption.

Mia is going to require a patient owner who can deal with managing her energy and her epilepsy - but anyone who takes this on is going to feel the rewards of her love and affection for years to come!

All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption. All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

To adopt or learn more about Mia, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description:
Disco has been in our care for just over a month and we are so proud of her progress. We would like to officially introduce this sweet girl as she is now available for adoption!

Disco is estimated to be around 8 years old. She joined MMDR after she became increasingly stressed by the small children in her home. It was a very difficult decision for her family, but they felt it was in Disco’s best interest to find a more suitable home for her. We enlisted the help of our trainer, Mydiek, to show Disco how to work through her anxiety when a stressful situation presented itself. Having Mydiek’s professional expertise allowed us to really get to know Disco and determine what areas she needed help with the most so we can place her in the best fit home. Her foster family was sent home with lots of homework, and things have been going so well! 

We are looking to place Disco in a home with no children. It was noted by her previous owners that she also didn’t get along with other dogs. Though Disco does have leash reactivity, she has been in the same space as other dogs during her rehab without issue. She would prefer to be the only pet in her new home. Her new family will be required to have training sessions with Mydiek and Disco will be placed on a 3 week foster-to-adopt basis. This will allow Disco time to adjust and give her adopters time to work with Mydiek so they can apply her training at home. 

Disco is a wonderful dog that just got off to a rough start. We have quickly fallen in love with her squishy face! If you think Disco is a good fit for you, you can submit an application for adoption. If you have questions, or are already pre-approved please e-mail our adoptions team at misfitmuttsdogrescue@gmail.com 

**Please note that we adopt all dogs out on a best fit basis and not first come, first serve. There will be no exceptions to Disco’s adoption guidelines. Please do not apply if you have children or other pets in the home**

Hey there! My name is Bam. I am almost a year old and a pretty handsome boy (if I do say so myself).  

I was taken to a vets office when I got parvo. My family didn’t come back for me. I was very sad and lived at the vet’s office for over a month. Then the SPSPCA found me a foster family where I could play and heal emotionally.  

At my foster home I have many brothers and sisters to play with.  I absolutely love to play with them.  My foster mom says I have a happy go lucky temperament. During the day when the people are gone I stay in a crate.  The mom says I never have accidents in my crate. At night I sleep in my own bed on the floor of foster mom and dad’s room. I am potty trained but I will need time to get used to a new place and your schedule. I am an excellent cuddler!  I love attention so much I tend to bite at your hands so you will pet me. I also try to use my paws to get your attention. I am learning not to do these things but for these reasons I would be best in a home with no children under 10.  If you are looking for a handsome cuddle buddy ask to meet me.  

I am looking for a soulmate to love me forever. I never want to be left again.  I am neutered, current on all vaccinations, microchipped and heartworm negative. My adoption fee is $150. I can go on a home visit with you for 1 week! If you would like to meet Bam,  please email adoptions.spspca@gmail.com

TO CONTACT THE FOSTER HOME, email adrukkerr@gmail.com/JBrock3@hotmail.com. DO NOT use the Petfinder form. Inquiries don't reach us.

Indigo, or Indi for short is located in NJ at the moment. He is a little over 1 year old. He’s very loving and affectionate and full of energy. Indi is a neutered male, 36 pounds and overall, very healthy and up to date with his shots and vaccinations. He is housebroken and loves going on long hikes in the woods. When overstimulated, Indi does have the tendency to get mouthy and sometimes he may try to snap or bite. He can be picky about dogs he gets along with, but he seems to be very comfortable with dogs that are smaller than him. He is good on and off leash, but beware he does not like moving mountain bikes or joggers. If you like to run, jog, or hike he can be a great partner. 

Even though Indi loves to hike and run, he’s also a great cuddle buddy too. He absolutely loves to snuggle and get neck and belly rubs. I work with dogs for a living and have been trying to get Indi adjusted to being around different kinds of dogs, but I’ve been having a lot of difficulty with getting him comfortable with the larger dogs. So being in a household with multiple dogs will probably not be the best fit for him. Ideally, he should be in a home with no dogs, cats, or kids. He may be ok in a household with one smaller dog or equal size dog, I have a 28-pound ACD mix that he gets along with well. Also, a fenced in yard would be a plus though it isn’t a requirement. He needs to be in a household with an owner that is very experienced with cattle dogs and is willing to work with him. Indi is a very sweet dog who has a lot of love to give if you’re willing to let him warm up to you! 

For questions, please contact adrukkerr@gmail.com/JBrock3@hotmail.com.

animal.description:
If you are interested in this dog, don't waste time with an inquiry! Fill out an application here to get the ball rolling...
https://pethavenmn.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/dog-adoption-application/

Here is more about Snider!

6-years-old, 85-pounds

House-trained: Yes – will likely need reminding of good habits as he learns his new environment

Crate-trained: Yes – sleeps all night in his crate

Health: Snider is positive for Heartworm and the following is very important – he is on restricted exercise until the end of January for recovery purposes and overexertion can result in complications – he will need to be retested for heartworm in June 2021 to ensure they are cleared. This will be the adopter’s responsibility. If still positive, adopter will need to work with their vet on treatment and he should receive Heartworm preventative for the rest of his life. 

Other Dogs: Unknown – because of his activity restrictions, he has not been socialized yet with other dogs, but he may be okay with one other dog in the home provided there is a very slow, controlled introduction and ample decompress time for both the dogs when in the new home

Cats: Cannot go to a home with a cat

Kids: Snider is very sweet and absolutely loves the kids in his foster home (ages 6 and 16)

Snider is a sweet and gentle giant who has had a lot of change recently. He can be anxious and timid, but he makes such wonderful progress each day. Inside, where he feels most comfortable, he is an absolute joy. Calm and gentle when accepting treats, he will add so much love to a home. He is still afraid of cars and loud vehicles and will take off towards the back of the house when he is startled. It is important to have him on a strong leash at all times while outside. 

Snider loves his soft, squeaky chew toys and takes them into and out of his crate each day. He enjoys naps and relaxation most of the day since he is on restricted activity. Snider loves having a family and will thrive if there is a human to guide him and teach him confidence and happiness. He loves to be involved in all things relating to his humans. Having slow introductions and decompression time will be important to him and help him to enjoy his new forever environment. He is a true Great Pyrenees and training / acclimating to his new home will need to be in line with his breed. 


His adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.
animal.name: Snider

Baby Rose’s adoption fee is $300 which includes her spay, microchip, fecal exam, and shots up to date. 

Please consider opening your heart and loving home to this affectionate angel!

As we are a rescue all of our adult dogs/puppies for adoption must be spayed or neutered. Although we make every attempt to have this done before finding their adoptive families, this is not always possible. Please speak with your adoption coordinator to see of this service has already been performed or they will explain to you if your new dog/puppy will need this service while in your care at no cost to you.

When emailing please include your phone number to help speed up the adoption process.   Also, for the safety of our dogs we only adopt within a 2 hour radius of Joliet, Illinois to allow our volunteers to do home checks if necessary.

animal.description:
Tux (and his doggie brother Baloo) came to MPR when their owner, who loved them very very very much, passed away leaving a grieving family trying to do right by his dogs. Tux is 6 years old and has had 2 ACL surgeries.  They should not require any further care - but this owner loved these dogs enough to properly vet them.  

Tux is not a fan of cats, does GREAT with older kids but kids have to be ok with a dog of his size and one that is an active bully breed.  He could easily knock over younger kids.  

We have not done a lot of dog testing yet.  He's a big guy, needs to lose about 20 pounds, and we're working on that actively now with lots of walks and low calorie food/treats.   

Tux has not spent much time on a leash as the old home had a doggie door and access at his leisure to a fenced back yard.  As such for Tux to be successful we are looking for a home or homes with a fenced in yard.  Also just due to his size a fenced yard is his best option.  

They love belly rubs, sleeping in a comfy human bed or couch (Tux was a spoiled fur baby!), and laying around. He is neutered and up-to-date on shots/vet checks. 

Please complete an adoption application at www.moshpitrescue.com and we will reply promptly to see if your home is a good fit for Tux!!!  

The dogs came in together but we are looking for separate homes for them.  Tux is a lot of dog - he's 6 going on 2 and active.  Baloo (his doggie brother) is 6 going on 16 and would prefer not to be alone...  

From the daughter: Tux was adopted from his previous owner at only 4 months old, when the young owner realized he didn’t have time for a dog. Tux was originally purchased from a Pit breeder in Chicago. He’s smart, sensitive and loving. He’ll sit at your feet at the table, and would prefer your lap on the couch. He also likes to sleep in bed with his person! He’s a bit protective of his person - he’s prefer to get the belly rubs himself instead of letting his dog brother get them, so if you give too much attention to someone else, expect Tux to wiggle his way in between you and the recipient of your attention. He loves belly rubs and plays tug of war (he’s strong and playful!). He has had two ACL surgeries and is completely up-to-date on all his vet needs. All of his vet records will come with him. Tux has not been regularly handled on a leash, but the few times he’s been on one (to the vet and back), he has handled it well. He does love to go for car rides...in fact, when he escapes from the house, the easiest way to catch him is to offer him a ride in the car - he’ll jump right in! He’s somewhat lazy but does get exercise in his fenced in yard. He has had one dog brother his whole life. He is probably not a good fit for smaller animals - especially rabbits and cats.
animal.name: Tux

animal.description: Dane is an absolutely adorable, tiny Chihuahua mix. He is lively and playful and gets along great with other dogs. She loves to play play play and would love another dog her size to romp around the required fenced in yard. She is dog savvy older kid friendly as her 70lbs of puppiness would be too much for young kids and small dogs. She walks well on leash, but gets excited to meet new people and dogs, we suggest a harness while walking. She can be very vocal so no apartments or condos. She is an active wiggle butt and would love to be with an active family, she is go go go, until it is time for bed, then she goes nicely in her crate.

She does have bad hips and is not a candidate for surgery, so she will do best on glucosamine supplements and Metacam. Her new owners will need to be aligned on this for her moving forward.
She will do best as the only pet and with no small children. She is a finicky old lady, and loves her people, but her world should be kept small. Her DNA results show that she is not a Border Collie at all, but in fact, a Heinz 57! If you think you have room in your home and heart for this special gal, send us a private message. She is fully vetted and up to date on all her vaccinations. She will make a wonderful companion for a quiet household. 

Roxy weighs 44 lbs. She is not for a home with lots of stairs and would do best in a dog savvy home. 

Roxy is located in Hamilton, ON.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Clay County Animal Rescue & Shelter is located at 14400 Hwy. 45 in Louisville, IL. Our phone number is 618-665-3005. The shelter is open to the public 1-3 Monday-Saturday. Sundays we are open 1-4 to the public. If those times don't work, please call to set up a time to visit.

The typical adoption fee for dogs is $150. It includes vaccination, deworming , spay/neuter, heartworm testing on dogs of age and microchipping, which is now mandatory by state law. Some dogs we discount to as little as $50 due to sponsorship. Some dogs we ask a higher adoption fee, which helps us recoup expenses on heartworm treatment on other dogs.

All cats are spayed/neutered/vaccinated/flea treated/dewormed and microchipped prior to adoption. Cat adoption fees range from $60-$100. We spay/neuter/microchip/vaccinate and deworm all kittens and cats, prior to adoption. Our shyer/less adoptable cats are classed as "barn cats" and are free with a completed/approved barn cat application, which can be found on our website.

For updates on adoption events and more pics of pets available, go to our website, www.claycountyshelter.com or look for us on Facebook.

animal.description:
NO APTS/CONDOS

NO CHILDREN OF ANY AGE

My name is Axel Rose and I am a handsome blue and white pit bull mix that is 8 months old! My favorite hobbies are playing with toys, getting pets and eating treats! I was picked up as a stray, I am so glad because that way of life was not a good fit for me. I prefer a life of luxury with soft blankets and comfy furniture! I follow my foster mom around everywhere so I would be a great companion for someone looking for a best friend. I love to curl up next to my human on the couch. One of my favorite things to do is play with my foster sister in the backyard. She can be kind of mean and bossy to me but it is no big deal! I do need an adult-only home because I don't like being pushed or pulled by my collar unless I trust you and know you won't hurt me. This is the only quirk I have and I promise I am the best boy you will ever meet!.

Potty trained and Crate trained. I am good in my crate while my foster mom is at work for 8-9 hours.
People and dog friendly!
Great on a leash for walks
Medium Energy level
Adult-Only home. No Apartments/Condos
About 35 lbs.
Cats: unknown
Needs: Basic obedience training, I am a puppy and can't help but jump when excited
Fenced yard preferred (4' chain link is fine)

If interested, please
complete the
Adoption Application
on our website at
www.NeedyPaws.org
and we will contact you.
Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

Our $250 adoption fee includes up-to-date vaccinations, heartworm testing and preventative, spay/neuter and microchip.

We are a 100% foster-based rescue and all of our dogs live in approved foster homes. We are dedicated to finding the best Forever Homes, and will perform home visits and conduct veterinarian and reference checks for each potential adopter.

animal.description:
Jack came from his one and only home along with Stella - he is 3 years young and about 35 pounds. He has been neuter, given his shots, and his rabies vaccine. He is ready for his forever home which needs to have another young/energetic/playful beagle in it.
*Note: Jack would do well in a home with someone young and strong that loves to go hiking, walking, and playing fetch. Someone who can work with Jack's energy and young adult dog strength.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Our newest and youngest chi mix (maybe with pug?) addition is Susie!  This 3 year old was terrified and snappy when she was surrendered to a crowded county shelter and took a few days in foster care to let us touch her, but once she bonds she’s a silly playful fun-loving girl.  She was overweight but doing well on her diet and exercise program and already getting around better.  She has luxating patellas in her back legs as is common in small dogs and the extra weight was putting more strain on her knees, so it’s extra important to keep the weight off of her.  
Susie is looking for a calmer adult-only home without a lot of people coming and going where she can feel safe.  She gets along with some dogs as long as they give her space at first and is even starting to play with them sometimes.  

Please email njwoof@cs.com for an appointment to meet her 

Due to COVID-19, we will not be holding our Sunday adoption events until further notice, but we can schedule socially distant appointments with a specific dog outdoors at our vet’s office:
VCA Morris Plains Animal Hospital 
3009 Rt 10 East 
Morris Plains (Denville on GPS) NJ 07950
Now is the perfect time to open your home to a needy dog!  Submit an application from our website www.secondchance.petfinder.com to speed up the adoption process
All our dogs reside in foster care in Northern NJ until adoption. We are a small all-volunteer organization focused on rescuing local dogs from area shelters, as well as accepting some surrenders and puppy mill rescues.

animal.description:
MEET GLITTER!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. She is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4512700.

Glitter is a very scared girl that doesn't know why she is at the shelter. She is terrified of the staff that is working with her and she just wants to stay and hide in her kennel. She doesn't like the leash and when she's in the play yard, she just wants to sit in the corner and try to hide. A very positive sign was Glitter interacting with another shy female dog in the play yard. She may do well with another calm dog that will help her to see that everything is okay. She will need a calm home and an adopter or rescue that is experienced with very scared dogs. She cannot go to a home with children. She will need a lot of time, love and patience.

If you think you can help Glitter, please come and meet her today! Please bring your calm and quiet dog with you to meet her too if you already have a dog at home.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Willa. Research the Pointer breed and you will find descriptions of me - I am not a dog, I am a family member. I am pushy, stubborn, energetic and anxious, loveable, velcro-dog, fun, active, focused, playful, willing to please. 

Don't let my age describe my energy level as I am still on the go and want to play. However do let my age describe my abilities such as potty trained. 

I love squeaky toys. For Christmas, I have asked for a bin FULL of toys. I carry them around in my mouth all the time. This is so much fun! If you are going to kennel me, I will protest. I will bark and bark if you kennel me - so no apartment living for me. I prefer a house with my own fenced yard where I can be queen and you can throw the ball for me. I don't want to share my toys with other dogs and I will let them know - remember, I told you I am queen. If other dogs are going to leave me alone and let me do my thing, then I can live with that. I am not about to live with cats though - nope, no thanks, not my thing. I am looking for a family for the rest of my life that will be willing to keep up with me and do fun things as well as go home and eventually relax, enjoying the comforts of a plush couch and/or bed. 

Age: Estimated DOB 3/6/12
Gender: Female, spayed
Breed(s): German Shorthair Pointer

Dog friendly: Doesn’t want to share toys; "please don’t be in my face"
Cat friendly: no

animal.description:
Update for Hope:
Hope is now available for adoption as the adopter has decided to wait. 
Hope requires a home that will attend training classes and where owner is home more often than not. While she does great with other dogs, she gets over stimulated with multiple dogs. With that in mind, she needs a home with either one other dog or by herself. By no means is she a dog that has aggression issues at all and she loves absolutely everyone. Applications can be completed online from our webpage at causeforpaws.net Inquiries will be forwarded to her foster mom.

Hope and her mom, Joy came into rescue after living their lives on a chain 24/7 Joy the mom, is heartworm positive and not yet ready for adoption. Hope will be available in the next week or so after her spay. Hope is said to be a Boxer/Bulldog mix and is medium in size weighing under 40 lbs. Hope has settled into her foster home and does well with her foster siblings but loves to play. Most of the dogs in foster home do not appreciate her energy as they are senior, small dogs. Hope loves everyone she meets and will require a home with a commitment to attend training classes. You cannot help but fall in love with this super little girl.
Hope will go to her forever home with her collar/leash, bed, toys, which she loves and probably has never had before, food to acclimate and her bowls. 
For more information on Hope please email causeforpawsrescue@gmail.com 
Applications can be completed online from our webpage at causeforpaws.net
Adoption radius is 100 miles
Adoption fee $300

animal.description:
Fanny is a dainty sweetie with puppy-dog eyes that will warm your heart! She over three years old and weighs around 40 lbs. Fanny would do best in a home that is patient with older or no children. She loves to sleep and follow you around, but she is nervous of sudden movements. It's likely she hasn't spent much time before SG as a house pet. She wouldn't mind a small canine companion and is fine with cats, ignoring them. Fanny does great on walks, she takes her time and sniffs the grass, and enjoys the breeze. She likes car rides and is quiet and calm. Give her a little time and she'll give you her heart! She will be a fabulous addition to a family that can provide patience, love, and lots of belly rubs.

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi -

My name is Zeke and I am here on the website through no fault of my own. My parents were retired and moving to a retirement community when they learned at the last minute that the community had rules against having large dogs. They had to reluctantly give me up - it was a sad day for all of us.

Now I am with my new foster family settling in quite nicely. My foster dad tells me that I am very smart and routinely practices my basic commands. When he takes me for walks, I rarely tug on the leash and practice good dog-manners. When I see other dogs, I am curious and say hi but continue on our path. I enjoy going to places with my foster family and like riding in the car.

You may notice in my pictures that my front paws turn outwards. I was just made that way and while unusual for GSD, it is common in some of my dog cousins like bulldogs. You can see in the video how much I love to play fetch and that it doesn't impede my ability to run and play.

I am very food and toy motivated and love to learn new commands and routines. It doesn't take me more than 3 or 4 times to learn new things. I know how important it is to be housebroken.

Hopeful that I have won your heart over and you are open to adding me to your pack! Please email my foster parents if you have questions! 12/21/20 11:13 AM

Kringle is a 10 month old shepherd/lab mix who is so smart and ready to keep learning! He is off to a great start with his basic training. Kringle would love to live with an active family who has another dog to play with. No cats. Loves big kids, little kids might get plowed over. While he would be okay living without another dog, he loves the excitement (and affection!) that comes with a larger family and a dog companion. 


Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
Little Lady is a gentle sweet soul.  She is an old gal who believes she’s earned her right to spend her days napping.  She sleeps most of the day away, occasionally waking to go outside.  Her bitty back legs are a bit weak so sometime she walks a little sideways.  She doesn’t seem to mind, but it makes stairs impossible.  Don’t fret, she has also earned the right to be carried to where she needs to go.  Lady likes to quietly observe those around her from her comfy cozy bed and leave the interacting to the young ones, but she won’t mind if you give her lots of pets and scratches.  She is mostly house trained, but sometimes…you gotta go when you gotta go!  No worries, she is completely fine wearing some bottoms, if you know what I mean ;).  Her cute little eyes aren’t as sharp as they used to be.  Bright lights and strong cold wind aren’t her favorite.  She is patiently awaiting her Doggle’s order to see if that helps!

She would love a forever home that will treat her like princess she is.  She’s earned it!

animal.description:
Sykes is a 1+-year-old miniature Border Collie mix who only wants to hug humans. He relates well with other dogs. Is current on shots, neutered, microchipped, and heartworm negative. Interested: complete and submit the Dog adoption application available on this page. HOME visit and FENCED in yard required. NO electric fences, and no exceptions to our fenced-in-yard requirement. ADOPTION fee and contract apply. Available for out-of-state adoption, adopter covers the cost of transportation. 

Our adoption process involves 3 steps. We only accept two applications per dog/animal. We evaluate both applicants before deciding which household is the best fit. If only one application is received we evaluate this application using the standard process.

First, we evaluate you on paper via the adoption application https://www.123formbuilder.com/form-5081187/. Or the form provided after his presentation on Petstablished. com. If you meet our requirements we schedule a home visit, we travel up to 1.5 hours from our location. On this occasion, we bring the dog(s) with us to your home. The purpose of this visit is to meet you face to face, and for you to meet the dog(s), as well as for us to evaluate your fenced in yard and if there are other dogs in the home to evaluate the dog to dog interaction. There is no compromise on your part to adopt and neither is there a compromise on our part to adopt the dog(s) out to you. If we determine that you are the best candidate for their adoption and you are interested in proceeding with the adoption we complete the adoption contract, collect the adoption donation, and provide you with his Veterinary records. We will not adopt out any of our dogs to a household where there is no fenced-in-yard (it does not have to be big, just fenced in) or where electric fences are in use.

animal.description:
*Please note - If Kona is still listed he is available. Please make sure to read his full bio to ensure that he is a good match for you. 

Meet Kona! a 6-year-old, 10 lb miniature Poodle blend boy. We all know that Kona is adorable but please read his full bio. He will need a very special adopter who will be patient and understand him. Kona is nippy and only wants small doses of affection on HIS timeline. He cant be approached or he will nip. If he walks up to you and jumps up or starts licking you, then he wants affection and will graciously accept pets. But when hes done hes done. Hes also very possessive of his space. Dont approach him while hes in bed or he will snap. This includes dogs getting too close to him as well - for this reason, Kona needs to be the only dog in the home. Because of this, Kona can not be adopted to a home with children. He drags shoes and clothes to his bedding area but doesnt chew on themtheyre like a security blanket for him. Hes not a fan of the crate so his foster family lets him stay out in their house when they leave. He LOVES being outside, he wanders every corner of the yard and looks for lizards, and is tough to get back inside sometime! Kona will need an adopter with a fully secure fenced in yard. Although he does love to take walks.

He is going to need a special adopter who knows they arent getting a cuddly lap dog. Kona has already been adopted and returned once. He really needs to find that special person(s) that will accept him for who he is and love him unconditionally forever. Kona is up to date on his vaccines, heartworm negative, neutered, and microchipped. His adoption donation is $300. If you think that you could be the angel that Kona is looking for and would like to learn more about him from his foster family, please visit our website www.PoodleandPoochRescue.org where you will find the application to adopt.

animal.description:
If ever there was a great little dog, it's Rink!! She loves squeaky toys and tennis balls, and can entertain herself by throwing them in the air and chasing after them. But she would much rather play with you!! Rink is quite fearful of men, especially those whom she has never met or those visiting the house. Her ideal home would be a low traffic household (not many visitors) and with a single female, female couple, or a female & male couple but the male must understand he will need to earn her trust and go slow!! Rink is a dog that may need to be put away when guests are over.

Rink is very high energy but she is so loving, obedient and eager to please. She is great in the car and good with other dogs, too. She is okay with children, although she should be homed with older kids who have dog experience as she can get easily startled. She knows how to "Sit" and "Give paw" & is a great size!

If you think this good-natured pup could be "the one" for you & your family, please fill out an application & be sure to ask for RINK BECK!

animal.description:
Sweet Rosie came to us in the worst condition you can imagine. As a senior, she was dumped in a shelter, in such bad shape that we didn't even know what color her fur would be. After a few months of love and care for her body and soul in a foster home, Rosie is flourishing! She is about 10-11 years old and she is a Shepherd mix. She is sweet and absolutely loves to snuggle on a couch or bed with her humans. She can get a bit protective over food when other dogs are around, but she is just fine with them if food is out of the equation. Rosie is incontinent and will need a patient family. She will reward you with love and absolute adoration. 

The adoption fee of $200 will include spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate/required vaccinations, treatment for heartworm and any other necessary medical treatment to assure a healthy new pup for your family.


IMPORTANT DISCLAIMER: Although we do our best to describe breed, since our pups all come from shelters we can not and will not make any guarantee on breed or size. We can tell you that they are 100% RESCUED! And that is the BEST breed!

If you are interested in adopting/meeting , please visit our website at www.starfishanimalrescue.com or you may complete the online adoption application on our Facebook Page https://www.facebook.com/starfishanimalrescue/app/134425496630143/?ref=page_internal Once you complete and submit your dog adoption application we will set up an appointment to meet this pup!

*please note that we are a foster home based rescue and we do home visits as part of the adoption process - we are unable to adopt to families who live outside of the Chicago and surrounding suburbs. Thank you for your understanding.

Located near Charlotte, NC.
Coco is a 7 pound, seven year old brown and white male Poodle. He was found wandering the streets and when picked up by Animal Control with  a leg wound wrapped in electrical tape. 
Coco is vision impaired but that doesn't hold him back! Within a day of living with his foster family he could easily navigate around the house. He found the water bowl, jumped on and off the couch, and most importantly discovered his foster dad is a pushover when it comes to handing out treats!
Coco loves to wander around the fence in the yard and to follow other dogs, he loves to follow his human around too.  While he has not exactly learned to play with squeaky toys he loves to hear them and his tail goes crazy with joy.  
Coco is a sweet, easy going little guy who loves everyone. He especially loves being with his person. He is quiet. I've yet to hear him bark. He is neutered and completely vetted. Coco does his jobs when taken outside. He does not let you know when he needs to go out so wears a belly band when inside. This special little guy is looking for a special forever home. Please call Mary Palmer at 262 800 3323. 
You can find our application on our website Http://malteserescue.homestead.com

animal.description:
Meet Georgie, our nesest Paws' project pup.  
This handsome 8 month old male pup is terrified and very undersocialized.  He had a zero chance of making it out of a rural shelter without a rescue's help. 
Right now, he knows one command..''house''.  When we call him he will try to avoid people but runs in the house or runs into his crate. We are not a fan of feeding in crates, but its the only way we can be assured he is eating enough on schedule.
At night when its time for bed, he will run in the bedroom with the other dogs and sleeps all night.  He will stay still once cornered to be picked up, but that is as far as we have got with him.
Would anyone like to work with Georgie, even for 2 weeks at their home? We are hoping that we can find a few people that would be willing to help Georgie become more socialized around people.  Short term, long term, whatever someone would be willing to offer this boy to help him become more comfortable around people.  He is VERY submissive. LOVES OTHER DOGS. This boy needs a lots of time, patience and compassion.
Paws Rescue 727-772-3935
*As always, Paws provides everything for our foster pups.

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

**Charlie Brown is looking for a forever home where he has at least one dog friend, a fenced in yard or a dog park close by, and a family that is around a lot**

Hi, my name is Charlie Brown and I am a 2ish year old hound mix that is as sweet as I am goofy. I love love love other dogs and people are pretty awesome, too. I have not been around cats, but my foster mom thinks I'd probably be fine with them since I'm a bit of a scaredy boy. 

I am a playful boy with lots of energy. I need an active home that will ensure I get lots of exercise and attention! I am potty trained and crate trained, but I cannot yet be trusted left out of the crate when no one is home because I have a bit of separation anxiety. I have been known to break out of a wire crate, so foster mom uses zip ties to keep me in! I do much better in the crate when I have another dog next to me or close by! 

Though I have lots of energy, I am also more than happy to take a nice long nap on a dog bed or on the couch where my human can pet me! Belly rubs are great, and so are snuggles. I also enjoy running around and playing with toys in the backyard. I am still learning what toys are meant for me and what ""toys"" belong to my humans. I am getting better, but for the time being you should put your shoes away where I can't reach them! 

I am currently taking fluoxetine (it's very cheap :p) to help with my separation anxiety, but foster mom says I've come a long way and that in the right forever home she doubts I'll need to stay on it longterm.

I am neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, have been dewormed, and am current on my flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. My adoption fee is $300. If you think I could be the one for you, please fill out an adoption application on our website. If you have any questions about me, please email the Dog Program Manager at laura@secondchancenc.org. Thank you!

Meet Hugo in Colorado:

This old man has been described as an Angel by those who know him, and he really is!!! His name is Hugo and he is the sweetest and cutest old guy. He makes the most adorable happy squeals, and is a total joy to be around.

Hugo is 8 years old and is partially blind. He would do best in a home with small dogs or as an only dog. He is house trained, loves people and has a positive outlook on life. He was surrendered to a California shelter, and has won the hearts of those who have gotten to know him, so we just know there is a lucky adopter out there for this special guy. 

We are partnering with Big Bones Canine Rescue to find Hugo a loving forever home. If you are interested in adopting or fostering Hugo, please email us at woof@olddogsnewdigs.com. And if not please help Hugo and share this post. Thanks!!!

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

animal.description:
Foster-to-Adopt me!

Hi everyone, it's me, Penny! My friends at OPR rescued me from the San Jose shelter at the start of the pandemic in April. I'm a total love bug, and I've never met a person I don't like, but I'm choosy about my canine friends and would do best in a home where I can have my pawrents all to myself. My favorite place to be is next to my humans keeping them company.

I love to go for walks and walk well on leash, but I can get pupset when walking past other dogs. I just need to learn that it's okay and that I have nothing to worry about. My other hobbies include sleeping in sunny spots, sniffing in the backyard, watching you cook, going for car rides, and being adorable. I don't even mind going to the vet! I don't really like to be left alone at home for long periods of time because I start to worry about my people. Can you blame me? I basically think humans are the very best! I would love to find my very own forever family to adore. Do you think that could be you?

FOSTER to ADOPT an option ..

To learn more about me and better yet, to arrange to meet me, please fill out this application: www.tinyurl.com/AdoptMeNow

Woof!

animal.description:
ADOPTION APPLICATIONS CAN BE FOUND AT WWW.SOHODOGRESCUE.ORG AND MAZEY'S ADOPTION DONATION IS $275.

Mazey is a 6 month old Australian cattle dog. She is a small girl at 25lbs and won’t get much bigger then that. She is up to date on her vaccines and is microchipped. She also gets monthly heart worm and flea and tick prevention. Mazey is a very special little girl - she’s also deaf! But she does not know the difference and she does not let it slow her down. 

Mazey is a sassy little girl that will need an experienced family (and a fenced yard with a physical fence) to really shine in a new home. She is smart as a whip and a sweet little firecracker! Once she is a little older she will make someone a great sport dog and hiking partner. She has started single jump work and started agility foundation for puppies. This girl is excelling beyond our hopes and watching her work through a problem is amazing. She absolutely loves training and would make a great demo dog for someone. She has great toy drive and food drive for training, and as is typical for heelers, needs a problem to solve. 

Mazey loves other dogs to play rough and tumble with her! She gets along really well with other dogs but sadly, no cats or small animals and because of her deafness (and typical cattle dog puppy nippiness!) needs a home with only adults or teenaged or older children. She is 90% potty trained and she is working on loose leash walking. She is getting better every day with this but does get excited when she sees people and she loves them! She hasn’t met a person she doesn’t like.

Are you ready to add a smart and sassy girl to your home? Please apply at www.sohodogrescue.org!

animal.description:
Meet Pepper . She is a 3 year old, 65-70 lb Rottweiler mix and is TRULY the sweetest dog. Pepper is very well-behaved, potty trained, doesn't chew and good with kids. She's good with most dogs but will chase kitties so a cat free home is best. Pepper is a bit of an escape artist so needs a secure 5 ft fence.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Pepper is the right one for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US!
We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Bourbon. 
About 6 months and Deaf. 
I am a pittie pup. 
The last time my foster mom weighed me I weighed in at around 25lbs. 

I've been working really hard on potty training. I occasionally still have an accident or two, but I'm getting better. I know how to sit and what settle down means thanks to my foster mom's sign language she came up with. I absolutely LOVE playing with toys. I can go for hours. I will get the zoomies and become a little tornado. I enjoy sleeping next to my foster brother all night long.  I go in the crate when no one is going to be home, I whine a lot but eventually fall asleep. 

I would do best in a home with a large yard, big enough for my zoomies. I get along better with dogs my age and size. I would prefer to go to a home with children 12+ or older. Younger children scare me. I am very curious about cats, but with my high energy I would probably not be an ideal friend for them. 

I am located in Columbus, Ohio and I am so ready to go to my furever home. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption policies and apply online at [www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt).

Visit [www.speakfortheunspoken.com](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/) will give you more information about our rescue.

***PLEASE READ*** WE DO NOT RESPOND TO PETFINDER OR EMAIL INQUIRIES. Please fill out an application on our website if you are interested in adopting this dog. We will only set up a meeting with the dog once you have an approved adoption application. We actively manage our dogs on Petfinder, the dogs listed are available for adoption. Our resident gentle giant is Titus. This sweet and gorgeous new guy has instantly won over all of the volunteers' hearts. He is easy-going and gentle with the kiddos. He is also playful with other dogs. Once he came out of his shell a little his tail didn't really stop wagging. Titus is a large boy but he is highly trainable according to his foster mom and very treat motivated. She says he is now potty trained and doing excellent with his leash walking and is also doing super well with crate-training. Titus is great with children but due to his size he would probably do best with children 10 and older as he could accidentally knock down little ones. Titus requests a home with a large couch for napping and snuggling but that is all!  If interested in meeting this handsome guy please ask us today.
Titus was super lucky and scored a wonderful foster home! He is now decompressing from shelter living and learning a whole bunch of new tricks as well as how to dog. 
For more information, please contact Kristianna (a volunteer with Jxn Friends of the Animal Shelter) via phone (410-924-1053) or email (ksaelensybk2@yahoo.com). animal.description:
Radar is undeniably appealing! He's a very moderate size...right around 40 pounds. He is very sweet and playful. Because he is blind we don't feel he'd be a good fit for small children. Though he has never been at all snappy, it is easy to startle him. He needs a safe home with a good routine and a little patience as we're still working on house training...he wears a belly band in the house and we think his recent neuter will help. He does now know what "go outside" means and he's great about going out our dog door to go potty. 

Radar was never given much in life and then he was abandoned in the country...a blind dog left to fend for himself. He deserves nothing but the best from now on and we intend to make sure that happens.

If you are interested in seeing if Radar might be a good fit for your home, please go to "more about us" where you'll find a link to our online application. Thanks!

animal.description:
Our poor Zeus had a rough start in life.  His previous owners didn't bother to feed him right up until the day they dumped him off at the shelter, not caring what would happen to him. Little did he know that was his lucky day!  Zeus has been doing great in his foster home. He has since put on some weight and has learned how much fun he can have playing with toys.  Balls are definitely his favorite!  Our boy loves people and  would do best with older kids as he is a "bouncing boxer".   In his foster home, after some further evaluation he loves all of the dogs, especially when they play tug of war with him!  Zeus is around 2 years old and 48 lbs, and has some more weight to gain.  He is crate trained but still learning the ins and outs of being a house dog and does have an occasional accident. Our sweet Zeus is now ready to find his forever home where he will be a cherished part of the family and never be hungry again.  Can you resist that cute face?!

If interested in meeting our handsome guy, please visit our website and fill out an application at:
LittleRaysofSunshineAnimalRescue.org    Zeus's adoption fee is $300

animal.description:
Duke
2.5 yo male
Brindle
45 pounds
Slow Intro to People
Dog Friendly
Kid Friendly
No cats, no joke
Leash & Crate Trained
Needs Companion Pal
fostered in Portland, Or

Duke here.......I currently live in a foster home, what ever that means. All I know is that I get to hang out with a family that has boy humans and pups I play with all day long. We play chase, tug-a-war, take walks, go on car adventures and more. When we are all tuckered out, I like to snuggle up to my humans and keep them warm. Occasionally I go in a crate when my humans are not home. I don't mind especially when they give me a chew toy with peanut butter. It's my most favorite cuz I know there is a yummy treat for me deep inside. Sometimes I get impatient and excited but it's only because am so eager to love love love love love love and play. I have been working on my manners and my foster mom and dad give me lots of love when I listen to their commands like sit, stay, wait, free, heel. I don't mind learning new tricks, the young boy in my home taught me how to shake and then I get a treat. When I think about my forever family, I think about, fun car rides, running, playing and eating yummy food. I would like to sit and watch TV with you. Cuddle with you. I also like belly rubs. My foster mom gives the best rubs. I do like to meet others in a slow and easy way just so I don't get too enthusiastic. My foster family say I am going to be an amazing dog for the perfect family. I can't wait to meet them.

If you believe Duke would be a great fit with your family, apply today at:

https://www.nwboxerrescue.org/adoption-form

If you would like to adopt him, fill out an adoption application on our website www.nwboxerrescue.org

Like us on facebook for more photos of this handsome boy, as well as other boxers we have available! www.facebook.com/northwestboxerrescue

My name is Calamity Jane and I'm a tough little cookie from the wrong side of the tracks, but you'd never know it because I'm just the sweetest thing. I LOVE belly rubs and am super attached to people. I'll follow you step for step and sit between your feet waiting for pets. I wasn't cared for very well before I came to the shelter so I've got some arthritis that makes me run and jump a little funny but I still get it done!

This dog is spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations and current on flea/tick and heartworm preventative. This dog has tested negative for heartworms and is being treated in our care. The adoption fee is $400 if your adoption is prepaid and final prior to your dog's arrival. An additional $50 will be charged on dogs that are picked up from our Southbury CT adoption center, adopted at an event or foster home in order to comply with CT HB 5368.

If you are a MA resident, your new family member is required to go through a mandatory 48 hour quarantine period at the Woburn, MA isolation facility.  Your new family member will be dropped off by our transport on Thursday and will be ready for you to pick him/her up on Saturday between 12pm-2pm.  An additional $100 fee will be added for any dogs picked up from the Woburn, MA quarantine facility in order to comply with MA Order 405-CD-12 and Order 1-AHO-05.  

TO APPLY PLEASE GO TO  www.cprdogs.com.  If your application was successfully submitted you will get a confirmation.  

After receipt of your application an adoption counselor will then be in touch to answer your questions about this pup, discuss the adoption process and get the ball rolling!  If you have not heard from one of our volunteers within 5 days of submitting your application, please email mollibo@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Spot is a big boy who knows how to sit, fetch and take treats quite nicely. He's close to six years old so no crazy puppy energy. 

Spot needs a home with a lot of experience handling large dogs. No first timers. He needs a home willing to put the time in to training him and providing appropriate exercise. 

Spot can be cautious in new situations and needs time to get comfortable, but it doesn't take him long. 

Spot is great in the car and loves rides. He is gentle with people, but loves to run and play. After play time, we feel he's a couch potato at heart. 

Though he would have to be the only pet in a home, he would be very loyal to his family. 
*****************************************************************************************************
Interested in adopting?

Due to COVID- 19 the shelter is closed to the public at this time.

We are still conducting adoptions, but with a few changes. :)

1. Submit an application through our website at wacshelter.com if you are interested in giving one of our shelter animals a home

2. We will schedule phone interviews once the online application has been processed.

3. If the animal applied for is determined to be a good fit for the home, we will schedule a controlled in person meeting with the cat or dog prior to the adoption.

*ADOPTION FEE:

$95 (cash only) and includes:

Spay/neuter
First vaccines
FIV/FeLV test (cats)
Heartworm test (dogs)
Rabies vaccine (if old enough).

*****************************************************************************************************
Additional questions?

Does this dog get along with cats? There is almost always an acclimation period when a new pet joins the household. We are happy to suggest a few ways to ease the transition. A new dog should never be left alone with resident pets though.

Does this dog respond well to other dogs? No dog loves every other dog. A proper introduction (meet and greet) would be required as part of the application process.

Is this dog good with children? The better question is how the children have been taught to handle animals. A dog will respond negatively if he/she is not being handled properly. We can offer suggestions on how to teach children to interact with dogs and pay attention to body language. Young children should never be left unsupervised with new animals.

*****************************************************************************************************
Want to help a real shelter animal by adopting a Mini Plush Pet from our limited time fundraiser? Check out our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/wacshelter/ for details!

animal.description:
Taz ACCT-A-78805
Intake: Stray
Sex: Male
Age: 5 Years
Altered: No

Hi there! My name is Taz! I'm 5 years young and neutered. I'm about 29 lbs and believed to be a puggle mix--though we can't be too sure since I was found as a stray. I was pretty nervous while at the shelter and stressed while getting kenneled which led me to having to a couple bite incidents. My volunteer and staff friends saw through my fear though, which led me to foster care where I've been my very best self. I'm very food motivated (hot dogs are my favorite!) and I've been told that I'm a fast learner. I've mastered "sit" "come," "look," and "in" (for when it's time for me to head to my room). I'm working on other commands like "off" and "leave it" for when I jump up for attention or try to taste a yummy street treat. ;)

I've been living with my 2 large foster siblings that are male and female pit bull mixes and it's been a blast! I love being around other dogs and enjoy play wrestling with my foster siblings. Some of my favorite pastimes include playing ball (I even bring it back to you), chewing on nylabones, and enjoying stuffed animals with squeakers in them. My foster parent says I'm like their little shadow that follows them around the house. I also love naps and being a lapdog. When it's time to go for a walk I get super excited and hop around like a bunny. I'm still working on not pulling as much on the leash.

I'd prefer a home that is patient and willing to go slow with me. Adult humans are my favorite. Tiny humans make me nervous. I'm a huge fan of positive reinforcement training and promise to be my very best self for humans that come prepared with hot dogs and yummy treats. I'd also really enjoy a home with another dog. Any size is cool with me--as long as they enjoy having a 29 lbs dude like me around. If you think we might be a good match reach out to my foster parent Rachel via email at rachellawbaugh@gmail.com

Videos:
Taz Takes Treats: https://youtu.be/8wqidPNdv0w
https://youtu.be/YWEF__RlysU
https://youtu.be/yueI9JCUSrE

Dog Meets:
Taz and Doug: https://youtu.be/IMLrb3UowEo
Taz and Doug 2: https://youtu.be/aijqDpr6IuU

Bite Details: 
(12/10) -- His slip lead had come loose, so Lifesaving staff member got a treat in her left hand to distract Taz while she went to readjust the lead with her right hand. She can't remember if Taz took the treat or not, but he bit her right hand and latched. Level 3B.
(11/09)-- Bit Animal Care Attendant last night while attempting to get Taz back into kennel. Bite was to finger, level 3.

Medical Observation:
(11/06) fully vaccinated and checked in

Behavioral Observation:
1/4 (per Foster) -- Day One in foster: 
For transport he walked into a crate nicely that I loaded into my car. Once at my place he got out of the crate and car with ease. I have him set up in a spare bedroom to decompress and have some space to himself. He knows sit and loves hot dogs. He pulls on walks, but it's manageable since he's small. He's not neutered yet and loves to mark on each post and tree. I have a pee pad set up in the corner of the room that he's already been using to pee.
Day Two in foster: 
He slept the whole night through in his room without a peep. Continues to pee just on the pee pads while inside. Does majority of his business outside during our walks. Ate all of his kibble for breakfast and dinner. He's heard and seen my dogs through the doorway and only had tail wags and loose body language. I spend time in the room with him throughout the day while working from home and doing a puzzle off work hours. He'll do some whining when I leave the room but he settles within minutes. I have toys out for him to occupy himself. He's enjoys stuffies and nyla bones. He'll rotate between laying in his crate and laying on a bed outside of the crate.
I haven't attempted to handle him much or even pet him. I'm continuing to respect his space and mindful of the issues reported about him while in the shelter. Honestly, he's surprised me with his best behavior so far.
Day 3-6 in Foster:
Taz continues to warm up in foster care. He's settled nicely into a routine and goes to the door when he's ready for walks. He no longer pulls as much on the leash. He's had loose body language and appears relaxed when seeing dogs and people from afar. His favorite activity is being 'kitchen supervisor.' He'll sit and watch as my roommate and I cook. When we eat he puts his puppy eyes to work while sitting nicely. When excited he'll hop around like a bunny. He's solicited pets and even rolls over for belly rubs. We've been cautious of handling him due to his prior sensitivities, but he's continued to ask for pets by leaning into us and using his head to nudge our hands. He's been relaxed, loose, and shown no concerning behaviors during any handling. He trades toys nicely and likes to carry his stuffies proudly.
Day 7-14 in foster:
Taz has continued to do well in foster care. He's allowed all handling and enjoying pets. He now asks for head massages and belly rubs regularly. He tolerated a bath with some peanut butter encouragement and really enjoyed the towel dry afterwards. I took him to get neutered at ACCT and he sat in the back nicely while tethered. I was able to place Taz in the surgery kennel with no issue and remove him after the surgery with ease. Vet staff said he was a very good boy. Taz continues to sleep through the night in his own room, takes treats nicely, and do well being left alone while rotating time being out between my resident dogs. I've started walk alongs individually with each of my resident dogs. Taz has been loose, friendly, and polite during walks. 
12/13 (Per Staff) --Taz participated in today's photoshoot. When I went to his kennel, he allowed me to leash him, and pulled to get outside. He'd gone a walk with a KA earlier. He was uninterested in pets and was given to a volunteer (blue) handler who was familiar with him and his issues. He was very motivated by hot dog treats. He took several treats from the hand. He participated in the photoshoot, and then was returned to kennel. While returning him to his kennel, hot dog treats were tossed on the ground which resulted in him allowing for his collar to be removed and the loop to be loosened so it could easily be removed in kennel. Once in the kennel, he jumped in and more hot dog treats were dropped. He ate them too quickly for the leash to be removed. Dropped more hot dog toward the front of the kennel, which allowed for leash to be quickly removed. Once removed he had already finished the hot dog treats and as door was shut, he jumped up hard barking and snarling. 
12/13 (Per Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Hard barking. Hard barking on approach but loosens when leash is presented. Takes treats greedily and is able to be leashed. Returning to kennel, switched to temp lead. Taz enters kennel without issue but then turns and starts snapping as leash as kennel door is closed. Did not attempt to remove leash.
Leash Skills: Pulls Moderately On Leash
Handleability: Aggressive/Unable to handle. Unable to fully handle due to behavior. Tolerates slow pets to rear with tense body but whale eyed and growling for any other attempted handling.
Tag: Did not attempt
Toys: No interest. No interest in rope toy or ball.
Color Level: Blue
11/30 (Per Staff) -- Easily removed from kennel, walked fast put did not pull through kennels. Sniffed around office. No interest in treats or toys. Solicited attention. Allowed handling. When stopped petting, jumped up asking for more. Easily walked back through kennels, but once returned to kennel started hard barking and showing teeth. 
11/19 (Per Staff) -- NRO, off BQ
11/13 (Per Staff) -- Taz participated in the photoshoot today. He was easy to leash in his cage and walked out without any issue. He appears very housetrained as he pooped only a few minutes after walking out of the kennel. He was nervous in the room, and he growled at the photographer when he reached forward with a treat. He walked up the dog ramp after hesitating at first. I had my hand near his rear and he growled when I moved it but was easily redirected by a treat and squeaky toy. After several photos he walked down the ramp and back to his cage. Right before we got to the cage he peed a lot, and did not want to go back in, and immediately tried to snap at the leash once he was in the cage and snap at the door, so I left the slip leash on him. 
11/06 (Per Vet) -- Fractious, QAR
11/06 (Per Finder) -- fearful, unsocialized to people, can be aggressive and try to bite if you attempt to pet him, pulls a lot on leash
