Bella is a sweet, 4 1/2 yo terrier mix, who is currently on 2 medications to control her seizures. She is not seizure free - and she has days full of spunk, and days where she is a little slower. She currently lives in a foster home with another dog, 2 cats, and a teenager. A quiet home, with older teenagers or adults would be ideal, as she has some mobility issues, and can be sometimes unsteady on her feet. She prefers if the animals and people give her space, and understand her personal boundaries. She will seek pets and wants to play on her own terms, but is not a 'cuddly' dog. She does sometimes chase her foster canine brother around the yard, but can get unbalanced at times. She does walk stiffly but does ok with stairs and when getting up from laying down. Bella will have an accident in the house if not taken out regularly, but her kennel is dry and clean every morning. She is food motivated, and does know sit. She can be sensitive to touch when trying to dry her off on a rainy day. 

Bella is looking for the special home to give her much love and patience, with all her quirks and unique health considerations. She will back as much in return. If interested in Bella, apply at: AHeinz57.com

animal.description:
Introducing Lilo!  Lilo is a handsome chihuahua. He is 8 yrs old and  weighs 9lbs.  

Lilo is listed as special needs because of a birth defect.  Lilo was born without front legs. He gets along just fine. His foster mom got him some wheels and he is learning to get around with them too.  He requires no special care.  He is just different.

Lilo is a sweet boy. He loves attention!  He is a cuddle bug and enjoys a good belly rub.  He loves being outside on pretty days.  He is great with other dogs of all sizes. He is good with children school age and above.  He is fine with cats as well.  Lilo does like to protect his bowl of food from the other dogs. He will grumble if they come near him while he's eating but it never comes to anything.  Lilo is a typical Chi.  He has some "stranger danger" anxiety with new people. With a little time and TLC he warms up and is loyal little companion.     

Lilo is fully vetted, up to date on vaccines, is neutered and microchipped. He is on Proheart 6 and Bravecto.

Lilo's adoption fee is $175. The adoption fee helps with costs associated with getting our pets healthy and ready for forever homes.

WE ARE NOT A SHELTER. WE ARE A NO-KILL 501-C-3 NON-PROFIT RESCUE: To see an animal, you must fill out an application first and then once approved, we can set up for you to meet the animal you are interested in.

Here is the Dog Application that you can copy and paste into a browser: https://fs17.formsite.com/waverlypetrescue/form028182466/index.html

Clifford was from an accidental litter in Kelsey, Iowa. Mom is spayed now and Clifford is a WPR dog. He is living in a foster home. He is now up to date on shots, dewormed, treated with Frontlline, and tested heartworm negative. He will be getting neutered in February and can be adopted after he is fixed. Apply now to adopt him and we will hold him for you until he is ready.

Clifford is 6-months old as of December 2020. Right now he weighs 50 pounds and still has some growing to do. His mom is a purebred Boxer and his dad is a black lab. Clifford is a sweet pup and very friendly. He has a lot of puppy energy. He is working on manners and getting housetrained in his foster home. He does well with children and other dogs. He has not been around cats.

Will someone please adopt Clifford and give him a forever home? $350.00 adoption fee.

WE ARE A NO-KILL 501-C-3 NON-PROFIT RESCUE. All donations are tax deductible. We do not have a shelter. All pets live in foster homes. We only adopt to indoor homes. To see an animal, you must fill out an application first and then once approved, we can set up for you to meet the animal you are interested in. We do background checks on all applicants. If you have assault, domestic abuse, or drug charges please do not apply. If you have questions, please send an email to waverlypetrescue@mchsi.com

All animals see a vet for shots and normal exams. If they appear healthy and there are no obvious health concerns, then extensive testing is not done. This is normal procedure for pet rescues and shelters.
Waverly Pet Rescue puts a lot of money into medical care for each dog and cat we take in. $350 is the average cost for basic care. This does not include if the animal had an injury, required extra flea / ear mite treatments, or needed extra days at the vet office.

animal.description:
Jackson is a Staffordshire bull terrier, black with a little white on his chest. He is 7 years old and 30-35 lbs. He is house and leash trained. However, we always say that our dogs need a refresher course when they join your forever home. He'd like an adult home- or with dog-savvy teens- where he's the only pet, and where's he active. He likes having a job; for example, he likes helping our disabled volunteer. He is obedient and knows commands like 'sit'.
He was in a home with a couple since he was a puppy. They gave him up because they had slowed down, but he hadn't! He still has a lot of energy. He was used to being an only dog, and would prefer that in his new home. They did take him to doggie day care, where he was fine with the dogs.
His family said that he had started getting territorial about their bedroom, and so we recommend that he sleep in another room of the house, and not go in the bedroom.
He's one of those dogs that just always has to carry his ball! Another favorite toy is his Bob's Big Boy figure.
Got his very nice young adult Dad, who has wanted a dog just like him for a long time. Came from San Jose to meet 'n greet and drive home with him. Sadly, Jackson came back to us because the Mom of the house became afraid of him; he nipped at her. If it had been anyone else in the home, folks would have worked through it. His young Dad is heartbroken. We'll be having consult with animal communicator to learn more.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *


Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

animal.description:
PLEASE DIRECT INQUIRIES ABOUT ADOPTABLE DOGS TO OUR FACEBOOK. WE ARE CURRENTLY UNABLE TO PROCESS APPLICATIONS VIA EMAIL DUE TO LIMITED STAFF. OUR CONTACT IS THROUGH FACEBOOK MESSENGER. https://www.facebook.com/REDRescueEveryDog/

Meet Twiggy! This darling girl is average pug size (estimated weight 22lbs in November 2020) and estimated to be 6 to 8 years old. This sweet girl came to RED 12.19.2020 after time in a foster home. She was a last chance for life dog out of Texas, so not much is known about her past, however we do know she had a rough life as breeder dog until she was no longer useful. When she was found, she was diagnosed with heartworm. She has since been treated, tested clear, and is now on preventatives. Additionally she has an enlongaged pallet (common in the breed) that causes her to cough if she exerts herself or there is pressure on it (she needs to walk in a harness). That combined with her being a flat faced dog means she needs to be in cooler temperatures and cannot go everywhere with you. Her caseworker can go more in depth on the vets notes regarding this issue. While in foster care she has shown to be incredibly kind and happy, she bunks with a shy Chi and gets along with everyone. This dog requires a fully fenced yard with a visible fence, as well as a small designated area (set up like a Precision Courtyard Kennel) for when she is left unattended.  We are looking for someone who is home often with pug or flat faced dog experience who will be loyal and treat her like the special pup she is. Adoption donation is $450.

THIS DOG IS IN FOSTER CARE IN POULSBO, WA. MEET AND GREETS WILL TAKE PLACE THERE AS WELL. 

REQUIREMENTS FOR ADOPTION:

- Securely and visibly fenced yard 
- Precision Courtyard Kennel 
- Pug or flat faced dog experience
- Preference to a home with a dog friend



ADOPTION PROCESS: 

If you are interested in adoption please fill out an application here: http://www.rescueeverydog.org/Adoption.php
Answers to the application MUST be sent via message on Facebook (we do not receive applications sent via email)

1. Once the application is received it will be reviewed by that animals caseworker. 

2. If your application is seen as a good fit to the pet you are applying for we will request photos of your fenced yard as well as your current crate or the crate you plan on purchasing. 

3. Once received we will schedule a phone interview with you to discuss the pet and the next steps, should a match be seen. 

4. Meet and greet/adoption 

PLEASE, CONSIDER SPONSORING THIS COMPANION ANIMAL IN NEED. R.E.D. RELIES ON DONATIONS TO SAVE, SUPPORT AND OFTEN REHABILITATE LIVES. WHICH BRINGS LIVES LIKE THIS TO THE FINAL GOAL OF PROVIDING A SAFE PATH TO A NEW FOREVER HOME. GO TO SPONSOR BUTTON TO HELP SAVE A LIFE! FOR MORE INFORMATION ON R.E.D. GO TO WWW.RESCUEEVERYDOG.ORG Mandatory fenced yard. No apartments. Some Condos and homes with a private use fenced yard maybe considered. No children. Adoption donation for this companion animal is $. Donations cover some of the care costs for R.E.D. animals. Like housing, supportive care, medical needs and food. All R.E.D. animals are spayed or neutered and vaccinated. Most are micro chipped with adopter registration included. R.E.D. is a 501 C3 and all donations support our life saving missions. For more information and to complete the on line adoption application on R.E.D., please, see our website at www.rescueeverydog.org. 
PLEASE READ ALL OF THE FOLLOWING TO APPLY TO ADOPT: Not all applicants will be approved for requested animals. R.E.D. reserves the right to refuse service and adoption without explanation. R.E.D. is the companion animal's advocate and will select the most suitably matched home/environment for the the companion animals emotional needs and management requirements based on each companion animal's breed(s) general needs and the unique needs of each individual animal in our care. R.E.D. requires all applicants and adopters to conduct themselves in a respectful and courteous manner. R.E.D. updates it animals adoption postings daily. If you wish to apply to adopt this companion animal go to the on line application at R.E.D.'s website www.rescueeverydog.org. and look under adoption. Before applying, please, read the following information. 
(1) Application, Phone interview, Home visit are required. Adoption Donations are generally $100.00. to 450.00 or as posted. Donations support R.E.D.'s life saving missions and medical and other care given.(2) R.E.D. Dogs are spayed or neutered prior to adoption, vaccinated for Parvo Distemper and generally are micro chipped. (3) You must be at least 18 years of age to complete the application or to apply to adopt a companion animal. For the safety of children and dogs and limited information on dog the dogs interaction with children- R.E.D generally prefers/requires children in adoptive home to be approximately 5 or 6 years of age and up unless otherwise noted in the dog profile. All children must be behavior appropriate with animals. (4) R.E.D. does not a ship animals to out of state adopters. Out of state adopters must come to meet the animal in person in Washington if approved for a meet and greet with a R.E.D. companion animal. Thank you.

The NMDR Rehab Team is working with Ace to help him work through some behavior challenges. He needs a family who will be extra patient with him, and who preferably has experience with large dogs. The NMDR Behavior Manager will talk to prospective adopters to explain the work we've done with him, and what will be the best home situation for him. To submit an application to adopt Ace, visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/

Fun Facts about Ace
Very friendly with people
Likes other dogs 
Enjoys sunshine and fresh air
Big goofy, happy guy

Challenges for Ace
Can be wild and jumpy, and sometimes play bites
Needs an adopter experienced with large dogs
Needs a lot of exercise
His family will have no kids younger than 16 years

-----
Prior to being rescued, many of our dogs have experienced minimal socialization. As a result, there is often an adjustment period when learning about life as a family pet. We typically do not adopt to homes with children under 6 years old; homes with older children will be considered on an individual basis. Common skills such as house training and leash walking will often take a little extra time. Patience, understanding and a gentle hand are a must. The great news is, most of these dogs come around rather quickly and being a part of their rehabilitation is an extremely rewarding experience. Learn about mill dogs and fill out an application at our website: http://nmdr.org

To submit an application to adopt Ace, visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/

She came to us as an abandoned dog left in a rental...family moved and left her there for days, poor baby; so she really enjoys being around her people, playing with other dogs and her toys, she's a very active girl...still has a lot of puppy in her! lol

Sassy is a good girl, she's house trained, will sit for a treat and will kennel up if needed.  She's spayed, microchipped, current on her shots and heart worm tested, so she's healthy and ready to meet her new family! :)    

If you're interested in meeting Sassy girl, please visit our website at, www.doggonerescue.com, to fill out our adoption application, that'll get the ball rolling! If you should have any questions don't hesitate to let us know, we look forward to hearing from you!

animal.description:
Fiona is in a foster home in Kent WA

***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them***

Hi there! Let's get the medical notes out of the way first and see if you still think Fiona would be a good fit :)

Fiona was in a foster-to-adopt home recently & they took her to see a vet and we discovered that she has a heart murmur. We do not know the severity at this time, but will be getting xrays to determine if she will require medication or not. Many dogs live long, healthy lives with heart murmurs and you would never know! We will pay for the xrays and are working on getting her into a vet at this time for a further work up.

Fiona, 1 years old, Female pitbull. Fiona is the sweetest puppy you’ll ever meet! She is one of those girls that makes the perfect best friend. She is a little shy at first and does take a little while to warm up, but once she does, she'll be your best friend! This means that she will require someone who will be PATIENT with her and allow her the time she needs to decompress. She loves car rides and is very obedient. You only have to show her once and she’s got it.   She is definitely a people person with a very loyal temperament. She would rather be with you than out playing with the others. She has a very calm, easygoing energy level. If you sit down she wants to lay at your feet (or sit in your lap!). She is house trained and has no problem being put in her kennel. Fiona is cutest when she’s burying herself in her blankets. She is very calm and quiet. It’s very easy to forget she’s there. She is dog friendly, but again, she requires SLOW introductions when meeting any new doggie friends. After being in her foster home for only a week, she showed some signs of being possessive over toys with other dogs, but was easily corrected and allowed for the toy to be taken away from her by her person. She has been cat tolerant but likes to chase them. Decompression is KEY for sweet Fiona. 

Due to Fiona's puppy energy we recommend a home with no kids under the age of 12. 

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time.

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Hi.  My name is Pedro and I’m sure you’ve seen me on Facebook.  The thing I most want from Santa this year is a home for Christmas.  This could be a foster home, a foster to adopt home, or just maybe, a forever home of my own!  Right now, I am at a nice boarding facility, but I really want to be at home laying under a tree and waiting to open my stocking.  I am an older guy -- about six years old -- and so am beyond the puppy stage and very calm in the house.  I LOVE people and want to be as close to you as possible.  I like to sit in laps, sleep in your bed, and give kisses (ok, I’m a bit big at around 50lbs for laps but I give it my best shot).  I need a home where I am the only animal because I just love people so much.  I got to do a sleep over in a house with a Christmas tree and didn’t touch it at all and I found out that I really like music.  If you play for me, I’ll go right to sleep at your side.  I am still learning how to walk on a leash – I mostly do great but I can pull when I get excited so having someone to work with me on that would be helpful.  

I haven’t had the easiest life.  I was a street dog in Detroit and just lost my foster home because of a situation that didn’t have anything to do with me.  The nice lady I did the sleep over with says that I am a sweet soul and will make the right person a wonderful and loyal companion.  My adoption fees are covered by the Un-Shelter and they will also provide free training assistance if my humans would like it.  I am neutered, micro-chipped and have all my shots.  I would love to get out of boarding and in a home so if you can help me in any way, I would show you my gratitude as only a loving older dog can.

Please  Email theunshelter@gmail.com if you are interested or have any questions!!!

animal.description:
Maurice is a 10 year old, 60 lb. male
The best guess at his breed is: Lab Mix
He would be good in a home with: Adults/Teens
He prefers a home without: Dogs, Cats, Small children

Maurice is a silly boy who always keeps the volunteers laughing. He is tennis ball obsessed, especially if they squeak. He has a medium energy level. He loves to play ball and tear up toys but also loves to snuggle.

He spent about a week at a volunteer's house and they said he was very well mannered in the house and is house trained. They could leave him home alone and he didn't get into any trouble.

Maurice know how to sit and is food motivated. He has already started to learn how to give paw.

Maurice should live in an all adult home as he can be possessive of his toys and will need a family who can work on this behavior with him. He would like to be the only pet.

--

Our hours: In an effort to limit the number of visitors at our shelter during this time, visitors are limited to approved applicants only.


Instructions on how to fill out our online application are on our website here: https://www.lighthouseanimalshelter.org/application-instructions

We are receiving a high number of applications at this time. Please be patient with us while we adjust to these new changes and keep in mind that our volunteers process the applications as quickly as their schedules allow.

We do not adopt on a first-come-first-serve basis, but rather by the best match between dog and family, although we will factor in the order of applications if there are equally good matches.

How you can help us process your application:
Please call all of your references (landlord, if applicable, vet(s) and personal references) before filling out an application to let them know that we will be calling. We are an all-volunteer program and volunteers often make reference calls from their cell phone. It will be a number your personal reference does not recognize. We understand most people will screen their calls from unknown numbers so please tell them to keep an eye on their voicemail and give the volunteer a call back at their earliest convenience. We may end up playing phone tag with your personal references but will reach out to you if we need further assistance in reaching them.

How we process your application:
Once we receive your application, we will check home ownership or landlord permission, personal references and vet references. We will reach out to you if we have questions during the process or if we are having trouble reaching your references either through email or phone. We will contact you when your application is fully processed to discuss how you would like to proceed with your application and to discuss dogs in our care who will be a good match for you and anyone involved in the adoption.

Our adoption fee:
Our adoption fee is $400 ($415 if paid by PayPal) which covers the costs of vetting (spay, vaccinations, heartworm testing, preventatives while in our care, deworming and microchip) and any boarding or transport fees incurred in each dog's rescue.

animal.description:
April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Come meet Ryker, he is dog friendly and loves all people. He does need training but will be a great family dog for the right family. No cats or small animals. Ryker is super active and energetic, will do best in a home that gives him a lot of exercise and attention. No young children and must have experience with large very very high energy dogs.

Foster notes- Ryker 1/31/21

Ryker is perhaps the smartest dog I've ever met. He didn't work out in our home for reasons I'll describe below but want to describe some of his wonderful attributes. 

He's insanely smart and curious. Needs intellectual stimulation, would love to work 24/7, almost never relaxes unless worn out (both physically and mentally). Ryker is incredibly devoted and loving to his primary person. He's very trainable, and responds to treats unless distracted. At first he was amenable to being crated, but as our situation became more stressful that degraded

He'd be best in a house with 2 adults (and not many more) who are experienced with training dogs (unlike us). Our family with teens coming and going was overstimulating for him and he got excitable, then would jump and gnaw at arms and legs. I believe he had no intention to hurt, but couldn't control himself, and couldn't stop. With the right person/ training I think Ryker would be an AMAZING pet.

I also think Ryker would be a great police dog, or search and rescue. He followed gopher trails that were underground (I think that's what he was smelling). I believe his hunting instinct is high- so would avoid small pets. Loves belly rubs and chasing balls, although he gets excitable.

animal.description:
STATE: NH
AGE: 4 YEARS
DOB: 5/13/16
WEIGHT: 85 LB
SEX: M
NEUT/UTD: YES/UNSURE
COAT COLOR: FAWN
DOCKED TAIL: YES
CROPPED EARS: NO
CHILDREN under 4: NO (NO HISTORY)
CHILDREN OVER 4: UNSURE 
SEPARATION ANXIETY: UNSURE
OTHER DOGS: NO
CATS: NO 
CRATE TRAINED: UNSURE
HOUSE TRAINED: YES
OBEDIENCE TRAINED: MOSTLY 
LEASH TRAINED: SOMEWHAT
MICROCHIPPED:  NO
ADOPTION FEE: $475

1/12/2021-Gunner has SERIOUSLY progressed. He is obviously food motivated, who isn't?! During walks, we carry his favorite treats and when a person or other dog comes strolling by Gunner has been learning to relax, sit and wait. He's a work in progress, but he's doing less lunging towards others and more patiently waiting for his treat. He's scared of the basement, loud noises and anything hiding in the dark - big scaredy dog for sure! Gunner has taken a liking to sticks, and his toys! He's finally learning how to play and enjoy life. Since the weather's getting a bit chilly, he is insistent on crawling under the covers and being the best snuggle bug there is Gunner has made many friends and typically remembers them - sometimes it takes some coaxing. However, he is learning that people are not bad and other dogs are just living their best life as he is. Within a few months, I think Gunner will be 50% less reactive to other dogs and be a respectable gentleman on walks.

12/21/20-If you're looking for a companion that enjoys long walks, naps and netflix - Gunner is surely your match!  Gunner is adapting very well! Gunner seems to thrive in an environment with a person to entertain him throughout the day. Recently, he met a new family friend and stayed with them for the day. When meeting new humans he is extremely shy and anxious. Once warmed up he loves every person he meets. The family friend expressed that Gunner seems to walk with a 'Mob Mentality'. He's usually looking around and thinking all the dogs are out to get him. On the flip side, Gunner is a scaredy cat. He runs and hides whenever there is a loud noise or something jumps out when he isn't looking. Gunners best characteristic is teddy bear-like cuddles. He will let you sleep on his back as you both take naps together and certainly doesn't mind snuggling under the covers.

12/16/20  Gunner is looking for a home for the holidays! Coming in at 85 lbs he is a big cuddly bear! He LOVES to get attention. Gunner has been in the foster home for 3 days now. He has become more comfortable and is showing his true loving colors. He seems to love pets and kisses, practically every 10 mins he's looking for attention. He is great at walking on the leash and doesn't pull too often. However, if he sees a squirrel he becomes extremely antsy. Additionally, he is aggressive and when he sees one on the walk he pulls, barks and attempts to interrogate them. I foresee this being trainable and with a strong individual he will be better around other dogs. 

12/13/20-Gunner has arrived into rescue, and after a very long day on the road to his foster home, is settling in. He is an owner surrender as he was having bad fights with the other dog in his home & at doggie daycare with other dogs. His owner said Gunner is a very good dog, he just needs to be the only pet. She also said he listens well, he's funny, goofy & well mannered. Please check back soon as we get to know him better.

Jordan is a 6 year old, ~90 lbs chocolate lab mix who is sensitive, playful, and has a happy-go-lucky attitude (his tail is constantly wagging all day, every day). This handsome fella is super sweet, attentive and affectionate with his humans (he is one world class cuddler and gives the best kisses). He is a medium energy dog who wants nothing more than to cuddle with you on the couch but is also down to walk a couple of miles or go on some light to moderate hikes to keep you nice and trim. Other activities that Jordan enjoys include playing with his stuffed animals, napping like a pro, playing fetch and being one giant lap/velcro dog with his humans! He is also house-trained, walks great on the leash, is non-reactive, follows directions/corrections well, and knows some basic commands (sit, down, wait, etc.).

Please come adopt this handsome boy so that he can have a loving family of his own! At this moment, Jordan will do best in a home without any young children or small animals. With an experienced adopter and after slow and proper introduction/socialization, he can be around mellow, even tempered dogs that are around medium to large sized.


You can see more photos and videos of Jordan living the foster life via Instagram: http://www.instagram.com/tail.of.two.bullies/.

She is very playful and loves to go for walks and enjoys the weather outside. Her fur allows her to withstand some colder temperatures, so she is able to enjoy playing in the snow. With that being said she does shed A LOT. So she will need to be brushed on a regular basses. Potential adopters beware,  black hair will be everywhere. Lola absolutely loves playing with toys, especially stuffed plushies. She is not the most graceful girl, she's like a bull in a china shop, she tends to be a little rough when playing so I don't think she would do well in a home with small children. Because she has a high prey drive, she probably wouldn't do well in a home with cats either. Lola is a cuddle bug and will come up to have her butt scratched. She's a talker, so she will let you know how her day is going and if she wants something. 
If you want to come visit with Ms. Lola fill out an adoption application and contact the shelter today!

*OWNING a pet is a life time commitment!  Please be ready to make that commitment before you adopt a pet!

We list the pets breed as the one that best matches the physical appearance, temperament, and personality of the animal-in some cases it's purely a guess. The NMDR Rehab Team is working with Ewok to help him work through some behavior challenges. He needs a family who will be extra patient with him, and who preferably has previous experience with dogs. The NMDR Behavior Manager will talk to prospective adopters to explain the work we've done with him, and what will be the best home situation for him. To submit an application to adopt Ewok, visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/



Fun Facts about Ewok

Super cute

Enjoys sunshine and fresh air

Quiet and gentle



Challenges for Ewok

Working on being brave with people

Scared of loud noises, new people, etc

Working on his social skills with other dogs, but sometimes doesn't get along with them



To submit an application to adopt Ewok, visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/



-----

Prior to being rescued, many of our dogs have experienced minimal socialization. As a result, there is often an adjustment period when learning about life as a family pet. We typically do not adopt to homes with children under 6 years old; homes with older children will be considered on an individual basis. Common skills such as house training and leash walking will often take a little extra time. Patience, understanding and a gentle hand are a must. The great news is, most of these dogs come around rather quickly and being a part of their rehabilitation is an extremely rewarding experience. Learn about mill dogs and fill out an application at our website: http://nmdr.org

Meet Grace! She is an 11 week old blue healer - terrier mix. We expect her to be small/medium size. She is a little pup with a lot of personality and is sure to be the queen of her forever home. When Grace is not playing hard with her foster sister she is the ultimate cuddle bug. Grace is good with other dogs and loves a furry playmate. This sweetie would be great with kids and other family members who can handle her energy. She loves treats and has already learned to sit. She is working on potty training and is very close to no accidents! She will sleep in her crate at night with minimal fussing but Grace would rather snuggle under the covers with you. This little lady is ready for a forever home!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information.

Puppies under 12 months - $300

animal.description:
PUGGLE, 12 years old, 28 lbs (needs to lose 8 to 10 lbs) -- NEEDS LOW TO MEDIUM ACTIVE HOME READY FOR SENIOR VETERINARY CARE

She's got a body like a backroad and a lump on her butt, and we're smitten. Twelve years old, 10 pounds overweight, and gray in the face. Hold. Us. Back. Ruby falls into the "our major weakness" category, which is senior and bumpy. This puggle was loved once, but her former owner has health problems that increasingly disabled him over the years, and after a long while without being able to give his pup proper care, he is now hospitalized and Ruby is on the hunt for her golden years forever home. She came to us reeking of cigarette smoke, with open sores under her tight collar, and with painful ear infections. She's well on her way to healing and slimming down now, and that butt thing (it looks like a tiny water balloon) is not particularly worrisome according to our vet's testing, but it may need to be retested and/or removed down the line. Ruby is an easy going delight in the behavior department. She's chill, tough to faze, totally housebroken, great with other dogs, and trusting. Also super treat motivated, which makes her an awesome photo model. She'll be happiest in a low key home with humans ready for the highs and lows of old dog care and where she can get a few gentle walks a day and plenty of opportunities to lie by your feet. Intrested in adopting? Please go to www.socialteesnyc.org 

Her Foster Says: Ruby is a giant potato of puggle goodness. That face. She looks up at you with those big dark eyes and that frowny mug...STUNNING! As shes settled in, Ruby has started to seek out our affection more and more often, coming over for scratches and pets...shes on her way to becoming a total love sponge! It simply takes a good scratch under her chin and down her neck for her to lift up her head and reveal that the frown in the center of her face is really just the middle of an enormous smile!

PLEASE NOTE: This animal is not at the Social Tees office all of our dogs and cats are in foster homes while they wait to find their forever families. :) If youd like to apply to adopt this pet, please complete an adoption application at socialteesnyc.org. Because we are a small team and receive hundreds of applications each week, we are unable to respond to every application and every inquiry email, but we do our best. Please have patience! If your application is approved, you will for sure hear from us. If you have questions, please take a look at the Adoption and Fostering FAQs etc. on our website as all common questions are answered there. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility as we work to save these innocent lives!! 

LEARN MORE ABOUT US: socialteesnyc.org; Instagram via @socialteesnyc; Facebook.com/socialteesanimalrescue

animal.description:
Buster is a cute little guy. He is 13 years old and around 8 lbs. He is house trained and leash trained. However, we always say that our dogs need a refresher course when they join your home. He came in with his friend Johnny (senior basset/dachshund mix) after their elderly owner passed away. Johnny just for adopted 1/16/21 and settled into his swell new home immediately. He picks which dogs he likes. He is used to living with adults rather than kids. We got him neutered and his teeth cleaned.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

Sweet senior gentleman in search of his forever home.

Pippin loves everyone he meets and enjoys spending short periods of time outside, so a secure fenced in yard is preferred. His former home said he was an escape artist, but he's been in his foster home for months and he hasn't made one attempt to make a break for it (4' Kentucky 3 board fence), so we feel confident in saying he was left outside alone for long periods before finding an escape route.

He pulls on a leash, so isn't the best walking partner. Pip is food obsessed. We don't mean that he's like the rest of us who've put on the Covid pounds, we mean he's obsessed to the point he'll walk through you to get to food. He's not picky, any kibble, treats or people food are must haves (although he'll turn his nose up at green beans). For this reason, we are looking for a home where he'll be the only pet. He's great with cats and dogs that he encounters, but his obsession with food can lead to fights

* 9 years old

* Friendly with everyone but needs to be an only pet

Meet Keeba!

This dapper gent is a 4 year old Boxer mix with a wonderful personality looking for a forever home for the holidays. 

Keeba is such a good boy! He is intelligent and eager to please. He already knows how to sit, lay down, and give his paw for yummy treats and is currently working on his manners. He is a big boy but for some reason seems to think he is a perfect lap dog.

Keeba loves a good game of fetch or tug of war. And he will be your best friend forever if you play with him! He has a ton of fun boxer energy, is super playful, and extremely loyal and protective of his people. 

Keeba does great with routines and consistency. He would do best in a home with a loving diligent owner who will continue to work on his training and keep Keeba mentally and physically exercised. 

Keeba has an infectious smile and he's really proud of his giant ears as you can see from the pictures. Although Keeba has a great personality, he is looking for a home as an only child with no other animals. Because of this, we know it may be harder to find Keeba the perfect home. I am going to make a fabulous family dog. I am eager to give hugs and kisses every single day for the rest of my life! Do you love puppy snuggles? Yes?! YAY!! Come to meet me soon so we can cuddle! Love, Clover

animal.description:
{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name: Digit
Size: ~Large range: 61-100 lbs
Adoption Donation: $250 (applicable sales tax included). Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other: Spayed Female, Vaccinations current, Microchip, Older considerate children only

Digit is super sweet and happy!!

Foster Home Feedback

*
Digit has allergies and requires 2 medications to control them, one is a daily tablet and the other is an injection given every 4-6 weeks. The daily tablet costs about $99 per month and the injection costs around $135 per injection

1/23/21: Digit has been with us now for over two months and we are really starting to learn her personality. She loves her sleep; she honestly spends most of her day sleeping unless she thinks you are doing something interesting that she needs to follow you. Digit doesn't like the cold. She will hold her bladder for a long time in an attempt to not go outside but she's never had an accident. She goes out and does what she needs to do as fast as she can so she can get back in the warmth. We were working on walks but haven't been out a lot since it's gotten colder out.

We leave her out of her kennel at night and she's good about sleeping in her bed, although if you wanted her to sleep in her bed with you she would definitely not turn you down. Digit does well in her kennel when we are gone. She is in there for some extended hours when we work and never rips up anything or has an accident.

Digit does well with our resident Chihuahua. Our Chi doesn't want much to do with her and Digit is good about leaving him alone. Sometimes she gets playful and tries to play with him and it's obvious she doesn't realize her size but listens well when told to leave him alone. She does well with our cat also. Our cat isn't very nice and perches above her and hits her but Digit doesn't retaliate.

Digit has always been friendly when anyone comes to the house and wants all the pets. In her previous house, she lived with 3 young kids and did well; she just again doesn't realize how big she is so older kids would be for the best. Digit is still on her meds for her allergies and is doing well with those.

12/10/2020: Digit loves people, she will follow you around the house and rest at your feet. She gets along with dogs and cats. She does well in the kennel. Digit is potty trained and has never had an accident with us. She is a pretty chill, low energy dog. She really enjoys relaxing in her bed or on the couch. She will get bouts of playfulness and loves a good game of catch.

Digit gets excited for walks, but they are a work in progress. She has protective/anxious tendencies. We have been working on some behavior modifications and she is very treat-motivated. Her bark is worse than her bite and by that I mean she never bites but has that low, protective pit bull bark. Digit has allergies and takes Apoquel once a day and does a Cytopoint injection once a month. She takes her pill very well though. Digit would love to meet you and show you how good she is at snuggling.To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
Corso experienced homes only***
Duffy is a 10 month old Cane Corso who came to us from the Philly shelter. This guy currently weighs in at  85 pounds. He has *a lot* of growing and filling out to do. He's ALL puppy in behavior. He loves to  run, is always doing zoomies, and can't get enough of this snow. He especially loves making those snow angels and living in the moment. He has no manners or training under his belt whatsoever and is pretty much clueless about any and all  etiquette. He is  extremely mouthy ( the hard mouthy that could easily result in bruising)  and is quite  powerful. He needs a strong and firm owner experienced with the breed (he loves to push boundaries and set the rules, which he cannot be allowed to do).  He *does* respond to those who take control with him which is great.  He is a big jumper and will fly into you at warp speed and easily knock over adults and keep going.  He has a lot of energy and will need some big outlets for  that in conjunction with the training . He's extremely goofy and will make you laugh often, but he needs a lot of work overall. The good news is he is still a pup and has a great personality under all that unruly behavior.  Once he gets some training under his belt while he is still young, and before he gets overly powerful,  he will make an excellent companion. 

He will come fixed, chipped,vaccinated, and move in ready. He will also have his cherry eye surgically repaired. 

***If you are serious about adopting, you must first complete and submit an application on our website. We will not do anything without a completed application. Do not contact us through pet finder or emails us as All info is contained here***

Please be sure to read all about our organization before you apply to adopt. If you are serious about adopting you must complete an application on our website. There is information on our petfinder home page and our website www.phoenixanimalrescue.com . Our adoption fee for adult dogs is $450. We will not adopt a pet to you if all of your current pets are not spayed/neutered. This is a non-negotiable policy.

animal.description:
Meet our cute and adorable bonded pair Coko & Karmina.

Coko is the 7 month old male chocolate English Spaniel. 

Karmina is the white female Westie Highland Terrier with Havanese about 3 years old young - Known as hybrid breed "Havaniese" . She is considered a Hypoallergenic.

They both love each other and Karmina looks at Coko as her son. They sleep together, they eat together and they play together. We would love for them to get adopted together but we are open to separate them if you have another submissive dog to keep them company and teach them the new rules of their new home.

They get along with all dogs and is being fostered with some cats; although they don't get them mixed; but she knows they are there -

Coko weights about 12 lbs and Karmina about 25 lbs.

Coko was found abandoned in a main highway, afraid, confused and almost got hit by a car.

Karmina was used for breeding and had multiple pregnancies.

As with all rescued fury kids; they are going to need training, love reinforcement; as you know they all come from a tough beginning on their lives and the art of adopting a rescued creature is to bring them to be the best they can be with love and patience.

Their adoption fee includes being spayed/neutered, they have received their 3 core puppy vaccines, dewormed, and a free health check up through a local participating vet clinic.

Ready to give them a forever home? Please follow the instructions and start with completing an application at the following link: http://aaofus.org/adoption-application.html

We are scheduling meet & greet adoption appointments and keeping a distance protocol. No appointments will be made unless we have received an application; therefore, we can match you with the best fit for you. In addition, to keep you safe and healthy as well as our pups that don't need to be handle by too many people. Appointments are scheduled late afternoons.

Please text at 619-576-0747 or email veronica.aaofusa@gmail.com or visit our website at www.aaofus.org and complete our application at the following link:
http://aaofus.org/adoption-application.html

Due to high volume of calls; NO PHONE calls are accepted at this time - therefore, please text us or email us.

This dog is with Survivor Tails Animal Rescue (STAR) please fill out an application: survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions. Be sure to tell them ARK sent you! #ARKforCharlieBoyBrown #JustSaveThem

Meet Charlie Boy Brown! He’s a 4-year old, approx 45-pound male hound mix located in Hull, MA and in need of a foster or adopter. If you want a handsome man around, then we’ve got you covered. With his dreamy eyes and spotted white coat with brindle patchwork, he is a looker!

Originally from the Volunteer State of Tennessee, Charlie likes adventures in the woods so he can do what he does best – sniffin' things out. He is quite the character and would love an active home that will take him on adventures like hikes and long walks! 

He also loves car rides and would make an excellent copilot for those boring errands. He’s young and active but he does come with an OFF switch because he is a champion napper! He is a good guard dog too and will alert you to people and dogs passing by. Apartment living isn’t suitable for his vocal iterations though. But hey, that’s what hounds do and Charlie Boy Brown takes his job seriously.

Ideally, he would benefit with structure and a daily routine in the home to keep things consistent! He would also benefit by working with a trainer in his new home to help with some basic training and eliminate some of that barking. He loves to learn and is very food motivated so training will not be difficult. Charlie Boy Brown’s ideal family is adult only and has experience owning dogs. Since he is a bit of the jealous type, he should be the only pet in the house! He is also wary of kids who come off as scary and unpredictable to him. Mature teens are ok though! 

So how about it? Want a partner for a walk on the beach or the piney woods followed by dinner and a nap? If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please fill out an application at survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions. Be sure to tell them ARK sent you! #ARKforCharlieBoyBrown #JustSaveThem

Meet Stereo. He is timid at first, but once he warms up to you all he wants is pets and scratches! Stereo is more fearful of men than women, but if given time, patience and love he will warm right up. He enjoys long walks, hikes and with training would be a great jogging buddy. He prefers to sleep on his doggy bed over the couch. Loves Happy Howe's lamb log but isn't a fan of peanut butter. Enjoys car rides and will act as a co-captain in the front seat. He needs a human with previous dog experience that has time to spend acclimating him to his new home. Up until he came to the rescue he had never been in a home before - so there is lots for him to learn about - sounds, smells, spaces, etc.
Stereo is crate trained, house trained, and leash/walk trained (ie does not pull and is not reactive on leash). Needs a calmer home with experienced owners. Does well with other dogs, but can be territorial of his crate and toys.

MEET MISTLETOE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in it's possession. She is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4521706.

Mistletoe is a stunning young boxer mix. She is not doing well in the shelter environment and very timid and shy. She will need a rescue or adopter who has patience and time to socialize her and bring her out of her shell. She's tolerated other dogs in the play yard, but hasn't played or socialized much because she's so nervous. She may do well in a home with another calm dog. It is unknown how she will react to cats. Because she is still learning to trust people she will be best in a home without young children. If you'd like to meet Mistletoe please visit the Maricopa County Shelter.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

To adopt this special dog, applications must be submitted. Please apply online: https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application/
Pope Memorial Humane Society is open by appointment only and has limited staffing at this time. Applications will be reviewed as soon as possible. Please, no phone calls. If you have specific questions, please email adoption@popememorialcvhs.org 
Please tell them ARK sent you!!!

Meet Mardi, a 2-year old, 49-pound American Staffordshire who resides at Pope Memorial Humane Society in Dover, NH. This beautiful white & brindle purebred has one wish and that’s a fur-ever home for the new year! She is spayed, healthy, up-to-date on vaccines, and now that she’s been DNA-breed tested, she holds her head just a little bit higher.  

Mardi’s favorite activities include walks, playtime, and nose work. Her food motivation has served her well in both work and play, and she is “busting her tail” on training that will help her be more settled around fellow canines. Winter is the perfect time to adopt Mardi, as shelter staff recently discovered she enjoys romping and somersaulting in snow! Additionally, she has a heart of gold, and loves being loved by people.

Mardi will need an active but calm home, as well as one with no children under 14. This excitable pup has also asked to be an only fur child. Shelter staff members have been doing positive reinforcement training to reduce Mardi’s dog reactivity, and her fur-ever family will need to continue working with her. Mardi is a special pup who’s been waiting four months for a home, so if you think you could be her person, don’t wait another minute to apply for this bundle of joy!

Applications must be submitted online: https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application/. Pope Memorial Humane Society is open by appointment only at this time. animal.description:
Can we play?
I am a happy boyand I love to play with my friends, whether they are human or dogs!I sometimes am a little nervousmeeting new people, and I am also nervouswhen new people come to the door. I will get more training to help me with this! When I am home, I love getting pet and will snuggle up close to get belly rubs. Smelling things is my favorite hobby, whether it be around the house or on walks! I love to be outside exploring the sights and the sounds of the yard, and I really love taking my human along on walks. I get very excited when I see other dogs and I want to go up to them and say hello. If I get too overwhelmed, however, I can be pretty noisy. I'm an adventurer at heart, so if I am left alone outside too long, I may get bored and decide to go explore the neighborhood, despite the fence! I'd dobest in a home withchildren 13 years and older.

General Socialization Notes:

 I'm a sweet boy and a little shy meeting new people. I do warm up quickly. I like my crate, especially if there is food inside. I love to play with other dogs. I am a smart boy and will love to continue training.

Does Sheriff like other pets?

I absolutely love to play with other dogs, it's one of my favorite things! We can get loud and rambunctious but it's all in good fun. I gotreally excited when I saw a cat on one of my walks and would need to figure out how I feel about them before committing to living with one.

Does Sheriff like children?

I haven't met any children while I've been with my fosters, but I like to jump, chase, and gently nip when I'm excited, so I'd probably do best around children over 13.

Favorite Toys:

I like Kongs stuffed with my favorite foods, and NylaBones. Tennis balls are also fun to chase but I'd prefer to be playing with another dog or human instead of an inanimate object!

Ideal Forever Home:

My ideal foreverhome would have another dog who likes to play, and a yard with at least a six foot fence! I am learning how to work for treats, and I would like to continue my undergrad in good boy-ism! A home without cats or small children would be ideal, along with a family who has a lot of love (and belly rubs) to give!

animal.description:
MAVERICK NEEDS TO GO TO A HOME THAT HAS ANOTHER YOUNG DOG THAT LOVES TO CUDDLE!

If you can provide this, continue reading about his story.

Maverick came to the rescue from a vet clinic in Billings that had been trying to find him a home since 10/1!!! Can  you believe no one wanted to snatch this cute boy up?! Us either, that is why we jumped on it when someone sent us his story.

He had been surrendered to the shelter in Billings, not once but 3 times, prior to being dropped at the Vet Clinic!!! He was dropped at the vet clinic to be euthanized as the shelter was going to do just that if he was dropped off again. Due to no fault of his own, he just got very talkative at night, and his family didn't know what to do and why he was doing it. Apparently they didn't know he needs to RUN!!

So the vet clinic reached out to us and we said YES!

He is really thriving in rescue. He runs about 5-10miles a day. He does get talkative when he sees rescue mom getting things ready for our runs. Otherwise he sleeps like a baby during the day and night!! As he was able to get all his energy out during the day! 

HE Loves the other dogs. Has free roam of the house when rescue mom is at work. Still kennels up when needed. He knows how to play fetch now, although maybe not his favorite thing. He loves to run, snuggle, and play with the other dogs. He likes to patrol the yard and loves that he has a dog door and he can go in and out as he pleases. He really is the sweetest!! Whoever ends up with him will be getting an angel of a dog with such a big heart.


If interested in him, please fill out an application and email it to us--located under the FORMS section on the website listed below.

www.pawstopeaksrescue.com

animal.description:
Mileena ACCT-A-81339

Bio: Hi, I'm Mileena! When I'm not sleeping, I'm pawing at my foster mom and dad for more pets. I love running around the snow, and although I get overexcited when I see other dogs, I promise that I just want to play. My favorite place in my new home is under my foster mom's lap, guilt tripping her into giving me treats. I am a gentle soul and tire easily therefore I cherish my time on the couch. Please reach out to my foster mom for a chance to get to know me.

Intake: Stray. APO Pick Up
Age: 4Y
Sex: Female
Altered: No

Medical Observation: 
12/21 (Vet Check)-- Patient remains very anxious in kennel. She is staying on bed, whale eyeing, and low growling. Was able to coax off bed to accept a treat which is an improvement from yesterday but not enough to removal from kennel. Will continue to re-attempt. 
12/20 (Vet Check)-- Patient is too nervous to be removed from kennel for examination of ears. Starting course of trazodone and reattempt daily.
12/19 (Intake Exam)-- Eyes - Irritated around eye
Ears - Possibly infected; dirty - was cleaned

Behavior Observation: 
12/22 (Per Foster Staff)--Kennel Presentation--Nervous. Came to kennel door when I approached, ears back but gave small tail wag. She is very food motivated so will approach if offered treats. Took treats politely through kennel door. Sniffed my hand and leash nicely, but dodges/backs away from leash. Eventually was able to loop her and she exited on her own. On return she stepped right into the kennel and I removed the leash easily.
Leash Skills--Pulls Minimally On Leash. Walked with tail tucked initially, after some time out of kennel walked confidently with tail high, minimal pulling on leash.
Handleability--Loose/Allows all handling. I offered her treats and she would approach every time, giving small tail wags. She initially was tense but still allowed handling. Allowed petting all over. Doesn't solicit much attention at first but will come to you if you call to her. After spending half an hour with her in the office, she loosened up considerably and solicited lots of attention by leaning against me, wagging her tail and laying her head on my arm or lap. She then spent almost an hour napping on a bed in the office. Go slow, needs time to warm up to people after leaving kennel but then is friendly and social.
Tag--Did not attempt. Toys--No interest. Very food motivated, ignored toys.
Color Level--Blue. TTA. Sweet girl, very nervous in kennel and difficult to remove from kennel. Does very well once she is out.
12/20 (Per Vet)-- Tense, hard barking, whale eyeing with dilated pupils, piloerection and refusing to come to door
12/19 (Per APO)-- dog showed Scared but to Be safe from dog we still used control stick on dog while leaving apartment dog had urine all over carpet by elevator, was able to bring her to truck and able to get in truck. As i took picture of dog she show simple command like sit or lay down looks healthy 


This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. This animal is not onsite. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact foster@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster. 

We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more! 

Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

animal.description:
Approved adopters can meet Pickles in her foster home. Pickles is reactive to other dogs on a leash and is coming back to us as she’s hard to manage in her previous adopter’s dog filled neighborhood. Please read her entire write up below. 

Adoption coordinator Kathy 

Meet Pickles! She’s a beautiful mixed breed dog who is 3 yrs old and weighs 45lbs. She was originally an owner surrender to a vet’s office in the south. She has medium energy and bonds quickly to her people. She loves being pet and being with her humans, so a home where she isn’t left alone often is a must. She lived with several other dogs in the south and was ok with them. Since being up here, she is acting aggressively to other dogs on walks. She will try to get out of her collar or harness to go after other dogs. She needs a home with a tall (at least 6 ft) fence that is secure and can’t be climbed. She can likely climb a chain link fence. If no fence, then an ideal home is one where she can be routinely kept away from other dogs. She needs a home where she is the only pet as is not good with small animals or cats. She’s house trained and does ok on a leash when not distracted by other animals,  but is strong and will need continued training not to pull.  She would do best in an active home. Despite everything written above, she is a very, very loving, people- oriented dog that would love a family to call her own.  Her adoption fee will be waived for the right home. 

Please complete an online APPLICATION if you wish to adopt.  Forever Home Rescue New England is a 501(c)3  non-profit organization. We are a network of foster homes in the South and the New England area. THERE IS NO SPECIFIC SHELTER LOCATION. If you wish to meet our dogs, you must first be approved by going through our application and screening process. Forever Home Rescue suggests obedience training for all puppies and dogs. All dogs are up to date on their shots, dewormed and spayed or neutered. Vet fees, transport fee and New England quarantine fees ARE INCLUDED in each dog's adoption fee. Also, any dogs older than pups--even if they are not marked housetrained in their posting---usually housetrain within a day or two, because most are used to living outside in the south and will prefer to do their business outdoors. Our dogs and pups are best suited for families with children 5 yrs old and up. If you are approved to adopt, please submit the $100 deposit by clicking on our rescue's name in this posting (Forever Home Rescue New England--in purple) which will bring you to a new page with the deposit link at the bottom.  STOP! If you have not been notified of your approval status do not make a deposit.

animal.description:
#Gorgeous, #Smart & the #Sweetest girl that you'll ever meet. Say hello to our big baby girl #Micah. She's a 4-5 year old #Rottweiler mix, who weighs in at 65 lbs. Micah enjoys long walks, spending time with her humans, loves movie night cuddle time, loves car rides, lives to please her human, enjoys playing with toys and is very good motivated. She does okay with other submissive male dogs when properly introduced, but can be selective and it's mainly with female dogs. She's non reactive to cats and will befriend them sooner rather than later.. Micah is 100% crate trained, 100% potty trained & does phenomenal on a leash. We'd recommend no children 10 & under. Although she is great with all people and craves human companionship along with tons of attention, Micah does like her own personal space. She knows all of her basic commands and is just a lover at the end of the day. Did we mention that Micah gives hugs like a human would and that she will smile on command when you say Cheese. 

Adoption #Requirements: No Exceptions!
- Fenced in Yard Required
- No kids under the age of 10
- No Female Dogs & would thrive best as the only dog in the home

Micah is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue. Her adoption fee is $350 & will include her distemper, rabies, bordetella, parvo, & lepto vaccines; deworming; microchip; heartworm test; fecal test & being fixed. Micah is currently on both flea & tick, as well as heartworm prevention. We kindly ask that you please wait until then to ask any questions.

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS****
 
With the Covid-19 Pandemic going on we are still doing adoptions, but please remember that we are all volunteers and safety comes first. With our rescue being based in the Metro Detroit area, all prospective adopters must live within the state of Michigan (which means No out of state adoptions). Please remember we are not a shelter and are 100% foster based. Once you submit your application, it may take up to 2 weeks for us to get back to you. So please be patient with us.

Again, we kindly ask that you please read the entire post to answer your questions. If you cannot follow the instructions properly, we will skip your application and move onto the next one. We kindly ask that you save any questions, comments or concerns for the phone interview. We kindly ask the following: No phone calls, No pm's, & No multiple emails- We are all volunteers and promise to get back to you within a timely fashion! 
 
Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.'
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingaHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com. If you do not have a scanner, please take a picture with your phone and we kindly ask that you sent all attachments into one email.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. If you are interested in more than one dog, please list your top 3 choices on the completed application.
5. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a vet Check. We always do a home visit. And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!

Thank you in advance for all of your love & support,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

animal.description:
Callie's looks are what many of our adopters want. Because of her appearance she's had a huge response but Callie is going to be a harder to place dog. She's complicated. She is VERY shy and VERY shut down! She's been with Marleys Mutts for almost 40 days. This is not due to lack of interest but rather because of our desire to allow her time to decompress and make sure we know as much about her as possible so we can place her in an appropriate home. 

Callie will never be what most people want or expect in a dog (which is happy go lucky). She may always be shy, fearful and possibly even standoffish long term. She has not bonded with any of the humans in her foster home but has come out of her shell a tiny bit when outside and with other confident/friendly dogs. Most adopters are not equipped to manage this personality trait. She has never shown any aggression with people just fear. Love and affection will not ""fix"" Callies issues and if she's pushed too hard with well intentioned affection she will likely regress into her shell even further. 

What Callie needs is a home that allows her to decompress and adjust at her speed and doesn't push social interaction before she's ready. This process could take weeks, months or in some cases years. Even once she's fully decompressed she may never be a ""people friendly "" or super social dog. Only time will tell us what kind of personality she'll have once her fear has decreased. We'd really love for Callie to have a quiet home, a patient family and another confident friendly dog as she's more dog oriented and dogs will help pull her out of her shell a bit quicker. Children make her nervous so a child free home would suit her the best. 

We are taking our time with her placement as placing her isn't the #1 priority unless the placement is the right match. She's much too sensitive to be bounced around from home to home if a placement doesn't work out. 

I know how eager families are to adopt but with some dogs the process just takes longer. We really want Callie to have that perfect fit. If you feel you can be the patient home Callie needs no matter how long it takes her to open up apply today If you are interested in adopting a Marley's Mutts please fill out an application at http://marleysmutts.org/adoptionprocess/

Karen is a sweet girl and an extremely loving companion; but she does need some time to build trust. She takes a little bit of time to warm up but once she does, she is absolutely full of love, kindness and power snuggles. She really enjoys snuggling and being close to people. She has come a long way and really benefits from being with another dog who she feels will love, protect her and show her the ropes of being an independent animal. She really enjoys running outside and has learned to play fetch and retrieve tennis balls by hanging out with her older, foster brothers. Karen is also a very low maintenance dog and really loves to lay in her crate and relax. She also redefines the word couch potato and has become a professional wrestler as her side hustle. Karen is the perfect mix of relaxing and being a couch potato to turning it up with some sprints around the yard, some backyard brawls (wrestling) and chasing the chuck it balls. She is an absolute love and will make a great addition to any home. As she is still skittish, she would really benefit from a fenced in yard as well as being with another dog. She has no issues with cats aside from wanting to play with them.

Please Note: All dogs are posted until they are officially adopted. This dog may have other interested adopters in line. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website at www.lasthopek9.org.

Questions? Please email adoptions@lasthopek9.org. For more photos, or information on upcoming adoption events where you can meet her, please go to www.lasthopek9.org or go to our Facebook page. Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

animal.description: Sugar Plum is such a tail-wagging, busy, playful girl. Outdoors, she loves playing in the water and hiking and sniffing in parks.
